.TH "ksh" "user cmd"
.SH "NAME"
\fBksh\fP \(em KornShell, a
standard/restricted command and programming language
.SH "SYNOPSIS"
.PP
\fBksh\fP [\(+-abcefhikmnoprstuvxCP]  [-I  | file ]  [\(+-o  | option ]  [\&.\!\&.\!\&.]  [-]  [arg \&.\!\&.\!\&.]  [rksh]  [\(+-abcefhikmnoprstuvxCP]  [-I  | file ]  [\(+-o  | option ]  [\&.\!\&.\!\&.]  [-]  [arg \&.\!\&.\!\&.] 
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
.PP
\fIKsh\^\fP is a command and programming language
that executes commands read from a terminal
or a file\&.
\fIRksh\^\fP is a restricted version of the
command interpreter
\fIksh\fP; it is used to set up login names and execution environments whose
capabilities are more controlled than those of the standard shell\&.
See
\fIInvocation\^\fP below
for the meaning of arguments to the shell\&.
.SS "Definitions\&."
.PP
A
\fImetacharacter\^\fP is one of the following characters:
.PP
\fB; & ( ) \(or < > new-line space tab\fP
.PP
A
\fIblank\^\fP is a
\fBtab\fP or a
\fBspace\fP\&. An
\fIidentifier\^\fP is a sequence of letters, digits, or underscores
starting with a letter or underscore\&.
Identifiers are used as components of
\fIvariable\^\fP names\&.
A
\fIvname\^\fP is a sequence of one or more identifiers
separated by a\&. and optionally preceded
by a \&.\&.
Vnames are used as function and variable names\&.
A
\fIword\^\fP is a sequence of
\fIcharacters\^\fP excluding non-quoted
\fImetacharacters\fP\&.
.PP
A
\fIcommand\^\fP is a sequence of characters in the syntax
of the shell language\&.
The shell reads each command and
carries out the desired action either directly or by invoking
separate utilities\&.
A built-in command is a command that is carried out by the
shell itself without creating a separate process\&.
Some commands are built-in purely for convenience
and are not documented here\&.
Built-ins that cause
side effects in the shell environment and
built-ins that are found before performing a
path search (see
\fIExecution\^\fP below)
are documented here\&.
For historical reasons, some of
these built-ins behave differently than
other built-ins and are called
\fIspecial built-ins\fP\&.
.SS "Commands\&."
.PP
A
\fIsimple-command\^\fP is a list of variable assignments
(see
\fIVariable\fP \fIAssignments\^\fP below)
or a sequence of
\fIblank\^\fP separated words
which may be preceded by a list of variable assignments
(see
\fIEnvironment\^\fP below)\&.
The first word specifies the name of the command to
be executed\&.
Except as specified below,
the remaining words are passed as arguments
to the invoked command\&.
The command name is passed as argument 0
(see
\fIexec\fP(2))\&. The
\fIvalue\^\fP of a simple-command is its exit status; 0-255
if it terminates normally; 256+\fIsignum\^\fP if
it terminates abnormally (the name of the signal corresponding
to the exit status can be
obtained via the
\fB-l $?\fP option of the
\fBkill\^\fP built-in utility)\&.
.PP
An
\fIarithmetic command\fP begins with a
\fB((\fP, and consists of an arithmetic expression formed by
all the characters until a matching
\fB))\fP\&. (See
\fIArithmetic evaluation\fP below\&.)
The exit status of an arithmetic command is 0 when the
arithmetic expression evaluates to a non-zero value and
is 1 when the arithmetic expression evaluates to 0\&.
.PP
A
\fIpipeline\^\fP is a sequence of one or more
\fIcommands\^\fP separated by
\fB\(or\fP\&. The standard output of each command but the last
is connected by a
\fIpipe\fP(2) to the standard input of the next command\&.
Each command,
except possibly the last,
is run as a separate process;
the shell waits for the last command to terminate\&.
The exit status of a pipeline is the exit
status of the last command\&.
Each pipeline can be preceded by the
\fIreserved word\fP \fB!\fP which negates the exit status of the pipeline\&.
.PP
A
\fIlist\^\fP is a sequence of one or more
pipelines
separated by
\fB;\fP, \fB&\fP, \fB\(or&\fP, \fB&&\fP, or
\fB\(or\!\(or\fP, and optionally terminated by
\fB;\fP, \fB&\fP, or
\fB\(or&\fP\&. Of these five symbols,
\fB;\fP, \fB&\fP, and
\fB\(or&\fP have equal precedence,
which is lower than that of
\fB&&\fP and
\fB\(or\!\(or\fP\&. The symbols
\fB&&\fP and
\fB\(or\!\(or\fP also have equal precedence\&.
A semicolon
(\fB;\fP) causes sequential execution of the preceding pipeline; an ampersand
(\fB&\fP) causes asynchronous execution of the preceding pipeline (i\&.e\&., the shell does
\fInot\^\fP wait for that pipeline to finish)\&.
The symbol
\fB\(or&\fP causes asynchronous execution of the preceding pipeline
with a two-way pipe established to the parent shell;
the standard input and output of the spawned pipeline
can be written to and read from by the parent shell
by applying
the redirection operators
\fB<&\fP and
\fB>&\fP with arg
\fBp\fP to commands and by using
\fB-p\fP option of
the built-in commands
\fBread\fP and
\fBprint\fP described later\&.
The symbol
\fB&&\fP (\!\fB\(or\!\(or\fP\^) causes the
\fIlist\^\fP following it to be executed only if the preceding
pipeline
returns a zero (non-zero) value\&.
An arbitrary number of new-lines may appear in a
\fIlist\^\fP instead of a semicolon,
to delimit a command\&.
.PP
A
\fIcommand\^\fP is either a simple-command
or one of the following\&.
Unless otherwise stated,
the value returned by a command is that of the
last simple-command executed in the command\&.
.IP "for vname\^ in word\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&. ;do list\^ ;done" 10
Each time a
\fBfor\fP command is executed,
\fIname\^\fP is set to the next
\fIword\^\fP taken from the
\fBin\fP \fIword\^\fP list\&.
If
\fBin\fP \fIword\^\fP \&.\!\&.\!\&.
is omitted, then
the
\fBfor\fP command executes the \fBdo\fP \fIlist\^\fP once for each positional parameter
that is set
(see
\fIParameter Expansion\fP below)\&.
Execution ends when there are no more words in the list\&.
.IP "for (( expr1\^; expr2\^; expr3\^ )) ;do list\^ ;done" 10
The arithmetic expression
\fIexpr1\fP is evaluated first\&.
(See
\fIArithmetic evaluation\fP below\&.)
The arithmetic expression
\fIexpr2\fP is repeatedly evaluated until it evalues to zero and when non-zero,
\fIlist\fP is executed and the arithmetic expression
\fIexpr3\fP evaluated\&.
If any expression
is omitted, then it behaves as if it evaluated to 1\&.
.IP "select vname\^ in word\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&. ;do list\^ ;done" 10
A
\fBselect\fP command prints on standard error (file descriptor 2) the set of
\fIword\fPs, each preceded by a number\&.
If
\fBin\fP \fIword\^\fP \&.\!\&.\!\&.
is omitted, then
the
positional parameters
are used instead
(see
\fIParameter Expansion\fP below)\&.
The
\fBPS3\fP prompt is printed
and a line is read from the standard input\&.
If this line consists of the number
of one of the listed
\fIword\fPs, then the value of the variable
\fIvname\^\fP is set to the
\fIword\^\fP corresponding to this number\&.
If this line is empty the selection list is
printed again\&.
Otherwise the value of the variable
\fIvname\^\fP is set to
\fInull\fP\&. The contents of the line read from standard input is
saved in
the variable
\fBREPLY\fP\&. The
\fIlist\^\fP is executed for each selection until a
\fBbreak\^\fP or
\fIend-of-file\^\fP is encountered\&.
If the
\fBREPLY\fP variable is set to
\fInull\^\fP by the execution of
\fIlist\fP, then the selection list is printed before
displaying the
\fBPS3\fP prompt for the next selection\&.
.IP "case word\^ in (pattern\^ \(or pattern\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&.) list\^ ;; \&.\!\&.\!\&. esac" 10
A
\fBcase\fP command executes the
\fIlist\^\fP associated with the first
\fIpattern\^\fP that matches
\fIword\fP\&. The form of the patterns is
the same as that used for
file-name generation (see
\fIFile Name Generation\^\fP below)\&.
The
\fB;;\fP operator causes execution of
\fBcase\fP to terminate\&.
If
\fB;&\fP is used in place of
\fB;;\fP the next subsequent list, if any, is executed\&.
.IP "if list\^ ;then list\^" 10
\fBelif\fP \fIlist\^\fP \fB;then\fP \fIlist\^\fP \!] \&.\!\&.\!\&.
[\! \fB;else\fP \fIlist\^\fP \!] \fB;fi\fP
The
\fIlist\^\fP following \fBif\fP is executed and,
if it
returns a zero exit status, the
\fIlist\^\fP following
the first
\fBthen\fP is executed\&.
Otherwise, the
\fIlist\^\fP following \fBelif\fP
is executed and, if its value is zero,
the
\fIlist\^\fP following
the next
\fBthen\fP is executed\&.
Failing that, the
\fBelse\fP \fIlist\^\fP is executed\&.
If the
\fBif\fP \fIlist\^\fP has non-zero exit status
and there is no
\fBelse\fP \fIlist\fP, then the
\fBif\fP command returns a zero exit status\&.
.IP "while list\^ ;do list\^ ;done" 10
.IP "until list\^ ;do list\^ ;done" 10
A
\fBwhile\fP command repeatedly executes the
\fBwhile\fP \fIlist\^\fP and, if the exit status of the last command in the list is zero, executes
the
\fBdo\fP \fIlist\fP; otherwise the loop terminates\&.
If no commands in the
\fBdo\fP \fIlist\^\fP are executed, then the
\fBwhile\fP command returns a zero exit status;
\fBuntil\fP may be used in place of
\fBwhile\fP to negate
the loop termination test\&.
.IP "(list\^)" 10
Execute
\fIlist\^\fP in a separate environment\&.
Note, that if two adjacent open parentheses are
needed for nesting, a space must be inserted to avoid
evaluation as an arithmetic command as described above\&.
.IP "{ list\^;}" 10
\fIlist\^\fP is simply executed\&.
Note that unlike the metacharacters
\fB(\fP and
\fB)\fP, \fB{\fP and
\fB}\fP are
\fIreserved word\fPs and must occur
at the beginning of a line or after a
\fB;\fP in order to be recognized\&.
.IP "[[ expression \^]]" 10
Evaluates
\fIexpression\^\fP and returns a zero exit status when
\fIexpression\^\fP is true\&.
See
\fIConditional Expressions\^\fP below, for a description of
\fIexpression\fP\&.
.IP "function varname\^ { list\^ ;}" 10
.IP "varname\^ () { list\^ ;}" 10
Define a function which is referenced by
\fIvarname\fP\&. A function whose
\fIvarname\^\fP contains a
\&. is called a discipline function and the portion
of the
\fIvarname\^\fP preceding the last
\&. must refer to an existing variable\&.
The body of the function is the
\fIlist\^\fP of commands between
\fB{\fP and
\fB}\fP\&. A function defined with the \fBfunction\fP \fIvarname\^\fP
syntax can also be used as an argument to the\&.
special built-in command to get the equivalent behavior
as if the \fIvarname\^\fP\fB()\fP syntax were used to define it\&.
(See
\fIFunctions\^\fP below\&.)
.IP "time pipeline\^" 10
If \fIpipeline\^\fP is omitted the user and system time for
the current shell and completed child processes is printed
on standard error\&.
Otherwise,
\fIpipeline\^\fP is executed and the elapsed time as well as
the user and system time are printed on standard error\&.
.IP "" 10
The following reserved words
are only recognized as such when they are the first word of a command
and are not quoted:
.IP "" 10
\fBif then else elif fi case esac for
while until do done { } function
select time [[ ]] !\fP
.SS "Variable Assignments\&."
.PP
One or more variable assignments can start a simple command
or can be an arguments to the
\fBtypeset\fP, \fBexport\fP, or
\fBreadonly\fP special built-in commands\&.
The syntax for an \fIassignment\^\fP is of the form:
.IP "varname\^=word\^" 10
.IP "varname\^[word\^]=word\^" 10
No space is permitted between \fIvarname\^\fP and the \fB=\fP or
between \fB=\fP and \fIword\^\fP\&.
.IP "varname\^=(assign_list\^)" 10
No space is permitted between \fIvarname\^\fP and the \fB=\fP\&.
An \fIassign_list\^\fP can be one of the following:
.RS
.IP "word\^ \&.\&.\&." 10
Indexed array assignment\&.
.IP "[word\^]=word\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Associative array assignment\&.
.IP "assignment\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Nested variable assignment\&.
.IP "typeset options assignment\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Nested variable assignment\&. Multiple assignments
can be specified by separating each of them with a \fB;\fP\&.
.RE
.SS "Comments\&."
.PP
A word beginning with
\fB#\fP causes that word and all the following characters up to a new-line
to be ignored\&.
.SS "Aliasing\&."
.PP
The first word of each command is replaced by the text of an
\fBalias\fP if an
\fBalias\fP for this word has been defined\&.
An
\fBalias\fP name consists of any number of characters excluding metacharacters,
quoting characters,
file expansion characters,
parameter expansion and command substitution
characters,
and
\fB=\fP\&. The replacement string can contain any
valid shell script
including the metacharacters listed above\&.
The first word of each command in the
replaced text,
other than
any that are in the process of being replaced,
will be tested for aliases\&.
If the last character of the alias value is a
\fIblank\^\fP then the word following the alias will also be checked for alias
substitution\&.
Aliases can be used to redefine
built-in commands but cannot be used to redefine
the reserved words listed above\&.
Aliases can be created and listed with the
\fBalias\fP command and can be removed with the
\fBunalias\fP command\&.
.PP
\fIAliasing\^\fP is performed when
scripts are read,
not while they are executed\&.
Therefore,
for an alias to take effect
the
\fBalias
definition command has to be executed before
the command which references the alias is read\&.\fP
.PP
The following
\fIexported\fP \fIaliases\fP are compiled into the shell
but can be unset or redefined:
