.SS "Tilde Substitution\&."
.PP
After alias substitution is performed, each word
is checked to see if it begins with an unquoted
\fB\(ap\fP\&. For tilde substitution,
\fIword\^\fP also refers to the
\fIword\^\fP portion of parameter expansion
( see
\fIParameter Expansion\fP below\&.)
If it does, then the word up to a
\fB/\fP is checked to see if it matches a user name in the
password database (
often the
\fB/etc/passwd\fP file)\&.
If a match is found, the
\fB\(ap\fP and the matched login name are replaced by the
login directory of the matched user\&.
If no match is found, the original text is left unchanged\&.
A
\fB\(ap\fP by itself, or in front of a
\fB/\fP, is replaced by
\fB$HOME\fP\&. A
\fB\(ap\fP followed by a
\fB+\fP or
\fB-\fP is replaced by the value of
$PWDand
$OLDPWDrespectively\&.
.PP
In addition,
when expanding a
\fIvariable assignment\fP, \fItilde\fP substitution is attempted when
the value of the assignment
begins with a
\fB\(ap\fP, and when a
\fB\(ap\fP appears after a
\fB:\fP\&. The
\fB:\fP also terminates a
\fB\(ap\fP login name\&.
.SS "Command Substitution\&."
.PP
The standard output from a command enclosed in
parentheses preceded by a dollar sign (
\fB$(\!)\fP)
or a pair of grave accents (\^\fB`\^`\fP\^)
may be used as part or all
of a word;
trailing new-lines are removed\&.
In the second (obsolete) form, the string between the quotes is processed
for special quoting characters before the command is executed (see
\fIQuoting\^\fP below)\&.
The command substitution
\^\fB$(\^cat file\^)\fP\^
can be replaced by the equivalent but faster
\^\fB$(\^<file\^)\fP\^\&.
.SS "Arithmetic Substitution\&."
.PP
An arithmetic expression enclosed in double
parentheses preceded by a dollar sign (
\fB$((\!))\fP)
is replaced by the value of the arithmetic expression
within the double parentheses\&.
.SS "Process Substitution\&."
.PP
This feature is only available on
versions of the UNIX operating system that support the
\fB/dev/fd\fP directory for naming open files\&.
Each command argument of the form
\fB<(\fP\fIlist\^\fP\fB)\fP
or
\fB>(\fP\fIlist\^\fP\fB)\fP
will run process
\fIlist\fP asynchronously connected to some file in
\fB/dev/fd\fP\&. The name of this file will become the argument to the command\&.
If the form with
\fB>\fP is selected then writing on this file will provide input for
\fIlist\fP\&. If
\fB<\fP is used,
then the file passed as an argument will contain the output of the
\fIlist\fP process\&.
For example,
.PP
\fBpaste <(cut -f1\fP \fIfile1\fP\fB) <(cut -f3\fP \fIfile2\fP\fB) | tee >(\fP\fIprocess1\fP\fB) >(\fP\fIprocess2\fP\fB)\fP
.PP
\fIcuts\fP fields 1 and 3 from
the files
\fIfile1\fP and
\fIfile2\fP respectively,
\fIpastes\fP the results together, and
sends it
to the processes
\fIprocess1\fP and
\fIprocess2\fP, as well as putting it onto the standard output\&.
Note that the file, which is passed as an argument to the command,
is a UNIX
\fIpipe\fP(2) so programs that expect to
\fIlseek\fP(2) on the file will not work\&.
.SS "Parameter Expansion\&."
.PP
A
\fIparameter\^\fP is an
\fIvariable\fP, one or more digits,
or any of the characters
\fB*\fP, \fB@\fP, \fB#\fP, \fB?\fP, \fB-\fP, \fB$\fP, and
\fB!\^\fP\&. A
\fIvariable\^\fP is denoted by a \fIvname\fP\&.
To create a variable whose
\fIvname\^\fP contains a .,
a variable whose
\fIvname\^\fP consists of everything before the last . must already exist\&.
A
\fIvariable\^\fP has a
\fIvalue\^\fP and zero or more
\fIattributes\fP\&. \fIVariables\^\fP can be assigned
\fIvalues\^\fP and
\fIattributes\fP by using the
\fBtypeset\^\fP special built-in command\&.
The attributes supported by the shell are described
later with the
\fBtypeset\^\fP special built-in command\&.
Exported variables pass values and attributes to
the environment\&.
.PP
The shell supports both indexed and associative arrays\&.
An element of an array variable is referenced by a
\fIsubscript\fP\&. A
\fIsubscript\^\fP for an indexed array is denoted by
an
\fIarithmetic\fP \fIexpression\^\fP (see
\fIArithmetic evaluation\fP below)
between a
\fB[\fP and a
\fB]\fP\&. To assign values to an indexed array, use
\fBset -A\fP \fIvname\fP \fIvalue\fP \&.\!\&.\!\&.\&.
The value of all
subscripts must be in the
range of
0 through 4095\&.
Indexed arrays need not be declared\&.
Any reference to a variable
with a valid subscript is
legal and an array will be created if necessary\&.
.PP
An associative array is created with the
\fB-A\fP option to
\fBtypeset\&.\fP A
\fIsubscript\^\fP for an associative array is denoted by
a string enclosed between
\fB[\fP and
\fB]\fP\&.
.PP
Referencing any array without a subscript
is equivalent to referencing the array with subscript 0\&.
.PP
The
\fIvalue\^\fP of a
\fIvariable\^\fP may be assigned by writing:
.PP
\fIvname\fP\fB=\fP\fIvalue\^\!\fP [\!
\fIvname\fP\fB=\fP\fIvalue\^\fP \!] \&.\!\&.\!\&.
.PP
or
.PP
\fIvname\fP\fB[\fP\fIsubscript\fP\fB]=\fP\fIvalue\^\!\fP [\!
\fIvname\fP\fB[\fP\fIsubscript\fP\fB]=\fP\fIvalue\^\fP \!] \&.\!\&.\!\&.
.PP
Note that no space is allowed before or after the
\fB=\fP\&.
.PP
A
\fInameref\^\fP is a variable that is a reference to another variable\&.
A nameref is created with the
\fB-n\fP attribute of
\fBtypeset\fP\&. The value of the variable at the time of the
\fBtypeset\fP command becomes the variable that will be referenced whenever
the nameref variable is used\&.
The name of a nameref variable cannot contain a \&.\&.
When a variable or function name contains a \&., and the portion
of the name up to the first . matches the
name of a nameref, the variable referred to is obtained by
replacing the nameref portion with the name of the variable
referenced by the nameref\&.
A nameref provides a convenient way to refer to the variable
inside a function whose name is passed as an argument to a function\&.
For example, if the name of a variable is passed as the first
argument to a function, the command
.PP
typeset -n var=$1
.PP
inside the function causes references and assignments to
\fBvar\fP to be references and assignments to the variable whose
name has been passed to the function\&.
.PP
If either of the floating point attributes,
\fB-E\fP, or
\fB-F\fP, or the integer attribute,
\fB-i\fP, is set for
\fIvname\fP, then the
\fIvalue\^\fP is subject to arithmetic evaluation as described below\&.
.PP
Positional parameters,
parameters denoted by a number,
may be assigned values with the
\fBset\^\fP special built-in command\&.
Parameter
\fB$0\fP is set from argument zero when the shell
is invoked\&.
.PP
The character
\fB$\fP is used to introduce substitutable
\fIparameters\fP\&.
.IP "${parameter\^}" 10
The shell
reads all the characters from
\fB${\fP to the matching
\fB}\fP as part of the same word even if it contains
braces or metacharacters\&.
The value, if any, of the parameter is substituted\&.
The braces are required when
\fIparameter\^\fP is followed by a letter, digit, or underscore
that is not to be interpreted as part of its name,
when the variable name contains a \&.,
or when a variable is subscripted\&.
If
\fIparameter\^\fP is one or more digits then it is a positional parameter\&.
A positional parameter of more than one digit must be
enclosed in braces\&.
If
\fIparameter\^\fP is
\fB*\fP or
\fB@\fP, then all the positional
parameters, starting with
\fB$1\fP, are substituted
(separated by a field separator character)\&.
If an array
\fIvname\^\fP with subscript
\fB*\fP or
\fB@\fP is used,
then the value
for each of the
elements
is substituted
(separated by a field separator character)\&.
.IP "${#parameter\^}" 10
If
\fIparameter\^\fP is
\fB*\fP or
\fB@\fP, the number of positional parameters is substituted\&.
Otherwise, the length of the value of the
\fIparameter\^\fP is substituted\&.
.IP "${#vname[*]}" 10
The number of elements in the array
\fIvname\^\fP is substituted\&.
.IP "${!vname\^}" 10
Expands to the name of the variable referred to by
\fIvname\fP\&. This will be
\fIvname\^\fP except when
\fIvname\^\fP is a name reference\&.
.IP "${!vname\^[subscript\^]}" 10
Expands to name of the subscript unless
\fIsubscript\^\fP is
\fB*\fP, or
\fB@\fP\&. When
\fIsubscript\^\fP is
\fB*\fP, the list of array subscripts for \fIvname\^\fP
is generated\&.
For a variable that is not an array, the value is 0 if the variable
is set\&. Otherwise it is null\&.
When
\fIsubscript\^\fP is
\fB@\fP, same as above, except that when used in double quotes,
each array subscript yields a separate
argument\&.
.IP "${!prefix\^*}" 10
Expands to the names of the variables whose names begin with
\fIprefix\fP\&.
.IP "${parameter\^:-word\^}" 10
If
\fIparameter\^\fP is set and is non-null then substitute its value;
otherwise substitute
\fIword\fP\&.
.IP "${parameter\^:=word\^}" 10
If
\fIparameter\^\fP is not set or is null then set it to
\fIword\fP; the value of the parameter is then substituted\&.
Positional parameters may not be assigned to
in this way\&.
.IP "${parameter\^:?word\^}" 10
If
\fIparameter\^\fP is set and is non-null then substitute its value;
otherwise, print
\fIword\^\fP and exit from the shell\&.
If
\fIword\^\fP is omitted then a standard message is printed\&.
.IP "${parameter\^:+word\^}" 10
If
\fIparameter\^\fP is set and is non-null then substitute
\fIword\fP; otherwise substitute nothing\&.
.IP "${parameter\^:offset\^:length\^}" 10
.IP "${parameter\^:offset\^}" 10
Expands to the portion of the value of
\fIparameter\^\fP starting at the character determined by expanding
\fIoffset\^\fP as an arithmetic expression and consisting of the
number of characters determined by the arithmetic expression
defined by
\fIlength\&.\fP In the second form, the remainder of the value is used\&.
If
\fIparameter\^\fP is
\fB*\fP or
\fB@\fP, or is an array name indexed by
\fB*\fP or
\fB@\fP, then
\fIoffset\^\fP and
\fIlength\^\fP refer to the array index and number
of elements respectively\&.
.IP "${parameter\^#pattern\^}" 10
.IP "${parameter\^##pattern\^}" 10
If
the shell
\fIpattern\^\fP matches the beginning of the value of
\fIparameter\fP, then the value of
this expansion is the value of the
\fIparameter\^\fP with the matched portion deleted;
otherwise the value of this
\fIparameter\^\fP is substituted\&.
In the first form the smallest matching pattern is deleted and in the
second form the largest matching pattern is deleted\&.
When
\fIparameter\^\fP is
\fB@\fP, \fB*\fP, or an array variable with subscript
\fB@\fP, or
\fB*\fP, the substring operation is applied to each element in turn\&.
.IP "${parameter\^%pattern\^}" 10
.IP "${parameter\^%%pattern\^}" 10
If
the shell
\fIpattern\^\fP matches the end of the value of
\fIparameter\fP, then the value of
this expansion is the value of the
\fIparameter\^\fP with the matched part deleted;
otherwise substitute the value of
\fIparameter\fP\&. In the first form the smallest matching pattern is deleted and in the
second form the largest matching pattern is deleted\&.
When
\fIparameter\^\fP is
\fB@\fP, \fB*\fP, or an array variable with subscript
\fB@\fP, or
\fB*\fP, the substring operation is applied to each element in turn\&.
.IP "${parameter\^/pattern\^/string\^}" 10
.IP "${parameter\^//pattern\^/string\^}" 10
Expands
\fIparameter\^\fP and replaces
\fIpattern\^\fP with the given
\fIstring\&.\fP In the first form,
only the first occurrence of
\fIpattern\^\fP is replaced\&.
In the second form,
each match for
\fIpattern\^\fP is replaced by the given
\fIstring\&.\fP When
\fIstring\^\fP is null, the
\fIpattern\^\fP will be deleted and the
\fB/\fP in front of
\fIstring\^\fP may be omitted\&.
When
\fIparameter\^\fP is
\fB@\fP, \fB*\fP, or an array variable with subscript
\fB@\fP, or
\fB*\fP, the substitution operation is applied to each element in turn\&.
.PP
In the above,
\fIword\fP is not evaluated unless it is
to be used as the substituted string,
so that, in the following example,
\fBpwd\fP is executed only if
\fBd\fP is not set or is null:
.PP
print \!${d:-\^$(\^pwd\^)\^}
.PP
If the colon (
\fB:\fP \fB)\fP is omitted from the above expressions,
then the shell only checks whether
\fIparameter\^\fP is set or not\&.
.PP
The following
parameters
are automatically set by the shell:
.IP "#" 10
The number of positional parameters in decimal\&.
.IP "-" 10
Options supplied to the shell on invocation or by
the
\fBset\fP command\&.
.IP "?" 10
The decimal value returned by the last executed command\&.
.IP "$" 10
The process number of this shell\&.
.IP "_" 10
Initially, the value of
\fB_\fP is an absolute pathname of the shell or script being executed
as passed in the
