The shell gives default values to
\fBPATH\fP, \fBPS1\fP, \fBPS2\fP,
\fBPS3\fP, \fBPS4\fP, \fBMAILCHECK\fP, \fBHISTEDIT\fP,
\fBTMOUT\fP and \fBIFS\fP,
while
\fBHOME\fP, \fBSHELL\fP, \fBENV\fP, and
\fBMAIL\fP are
not set at all by the shell (although
\fBHOME\fP \fIis\^\fP set by
\fIlogin\fP(1))\&. On some systems
\fBMAIL\fP and
\fBSHELL\fP are also
set by
\fIlogin\fP(1)\&.
.SS "Field Splitting"
.PP
After parameter expansion and command substitution,
the results of substitutions are scanned for the field separator
characters (those found in
\fBIFS\^\fP)
and split into distinct fields where such characters are found\&.
Explicit null fields (\^\fB"\^"\fP or \fB(fm\^(fm\fP\^) are retained\&.
Implicit null fields
(those resulting from
\fIparameters\^\fP that have no values or command substitutions with no output) are removed\&.
.SS "File Name Generation\&."
.PP
Following splitting, each field is scanned for the characters
\fB*\fP, \fB?\fP, \fB(\fP, and
\fB[\!\^\fP unless the
\fB-f\fP option has been set\&.
If one of these characters appears
then the word is regarded as a
\fIpattern\fP\&. Each file name component that contains any pattern character
is replaced with a lexicographically sorted set of names
that matches the pattern
from
that directory\&.
If no file name is found that matches the pattern, then
that component of the filename is left unchanged\&.
If
\fBFIGNORE\fP is set,
then each file name component
that matches the pattern defined by the value of
\fBFIGNORE\fP is ignored when generating the matching filenames\&.
The names
\&. and
\fB\&.\&.\fP are also ignored\&.
If
\fBFIGNORE\fP is not set,
the character
\&. at the start of each file name component
will be ignored unless the first character of the pattern
corresponding to this component is the character
\&. itself\&.
Note, that for other
uses of pattern matching the
\fB/\fP and
\&. are not treated specially\&.
.IP "*" 10
Matches any string, including the null string\&.
.IP "?" 10
Matches any single character\&.
.IP "\^\&.\!\&.\!\&.\^" 10
Matches any one of the enclosed characters\&.
A pair of characters separated by
\fB-\fP matches any
character lexically between the pair, inclusive\&.
If the first character following the opening
\fB[\!\^\fP is a
\fB!\fP then any character not enclosed is matched\&.
A
\fB-\fP can be included in the character set by putting it as the
first or last character\&.
Within
\fB[\!\^\fP and
\fB\!]\^\fP character classes can be specified with the syntax
\fB[:\fP\fIclass\fP\fB:]\fP
where class is one of the following:
.IP "" 10
\fBalnum alpha cntrl digit graph lower print punct space upper xdigit\fP
.PP
A
\fIpattern-list\fP is a list of one or more patterns separated from each other
with a
\fB\(or\fP\&. Composite patterns can be formed with one or more of the following:
.IP "?(pattern-list\^)" 10
Optionally matches any one of the given patterns\&.
.IP "*(pattern-list\^)" 10
Matches zero or more occurrences of the given patterns\&.
.IP "+(pattern-list\^)" 10
Matches one or more occurrences of the given patterns\&.
.IP "@(pattern-list\^)" 10
Matches exactly one of the given patterns\&.
.IP "!(pattern-list\^)" 10
Matches anything except one of the given patterns\&.
.SS "Quoting\&."
.PP
Each of the
\fImetacharacters\^\fP listed earlier (see
\fIDefinitions\^\fP above)
has a special meaning to the shell
and causes termination of a word unless quoted\&.
A character may be
\fIquoted\^\fP (i\&.e\&., made to stand for itself)
by preceding
it with a
\fB\e\fP\&. The pair
\fB\enew-line\fP is removed\&.
All characters enclosed between a pair of single quote marks
(\^\fB\&'\^\&'\fP\^)
that is not preceded by a
\fB$\fP are quoted\&.
A single quote cannot appear within the single quotes\&.
A single quoted string preceded an unquoted
\fB$\fP is processed as an ANSI-C string
except that
\fB\e0\fP within the string causes the remainder of the
string to be ignored and
\fB\eE\fP is equivalent to the escape character
(ascii
\fB033\fP)\&. Inside double quote marks
(\fB"\^"\fP),
parameter and command substitution occur and
\fB\e\fP quotes the characters
\fB\e\fP, \fB`\fP, \fB"\fP,
and
\fB$\fP\&. The meaning of
\fB$*\fP and
\fB$@\fP is identical when not quoted or when used as a variable assignment value
or as a file name\&.
However, when used as a command argument,
\fB"$*"
is equivalent to\fP \fB"$1\fP\fId\fP\fB\!$2\fP\fId\fP\!\&.\!\&.\!\&.\fB"\fP,
where
\fId\fP is the first character of the
\fBIFS\fP variable, whereas
\fB"$@"
is equivalent to\fP \fB"$1"\!\fP \fB"$2"\!
\&.\!\&.\!\&.\^\&.
Inside grave quote marks
(\fP\fB`\^`\fP),
\fB\e\fP quotes the characters
\fB\e\fP, \fB`\fP, and
\fB$\fP\&. If the grave quotes occur within double quotes then
\fB\e\fP also quotes the character
\fB"\fP\&.
.PP
The special meaning of reserved words or aliases can be removed by quoting any
character of the reserved word\&.
The recognition of function names or built-in command names listed below
cannot be altered by quoting them\&.
.SS "Arithmetic Evaluation\&."
.PP
The shell performs arithmetic evaluation for
arithmetic substitution, to evaluate an arithmetic command,
to evaluate an indexed array subscript,
and to evaluate arguments to
the built-in commands
\fBshift\^\fP and
\fBlet\fP\&. Evaluations are performed using
double precision floating point
arithmetic\&.
Floating point constants follow the ANSI-C programming language
conventions\&.
Integer constants are of the form
[\!\fIbase\fP\fB#\^\fP\!]\fIn\^\fP
where
\fIbase\^\fP is a decimal number between two and sixty-four
representing the arithmetic base
and
\fIn\^\fP is a number in that base\&.
The digits above 9 are represented
by the lower case characters, the upper case characters,
\fB@\fP, and
\fB_\fP respectively\&.
For bases less than 36, upper and lower case
character can be used interchangeably\&.
If
\fIbase\^\fP is omitted
then base 10 is used\&.
.PP
An arithmetic expression uses the same syntax, precedence, and
associativity of
expression as the C language\&.
All the C language operators
that apply to floating point quantities can be used\&.
In addition, when the value of an arithmetic variable
or sub-expression can be represented as a long integer,
all C language integer arithmetic operations can be performed\&.
Variables can be referenced by name within an arithmetic expression
without using the parameter expansion syntax\&.
When a variable is referenced, its value is evaluated as
an arithmetic expression\&.
The following math library functions can be used with an arithmetic
expression:
.PP
\fBabs acos asin atan cos cosh exp int log sin sinh sqrt tan tanh\fP
.PP
An internal representation of a
\fIvariable\^\fP as a double precision floating point can be specified with the
\fB-E\fP [\!\fIn\^\fP\!]
or
\fB-F\fP [\!\fIn\^\fP\!]
option of the
\fBtypeset\fP special built-in command\&.
The
\fB-E\fP option causes the expansion of the value to be represented using
scientific notation when it is expanded\&.
The optional option argument
\fIn\fP defines the number of significant figures\&.
The
\fB-F\fP option causes the expansion to be represented as a floating decimal number
when it is expanded\&.
The optional option argument
\fIn\fP defines the number of places after the decimal point in this case\&.
.PP
An internal integer representation of a
\fIvariable\^\fP can be specified with the
\fB-i\fP [\!\fIn\^\fP\!]
option of the
\fBtypeset\fP special built-in command\&.
The optional option argument
\fIn\fP specifies an arithmetic base to be used when expanding the variable\&.
If you do not specify an arithmetic base,
the first assignment to the
variable determines the arithmetic base\&.
.PP
Arithmetic evaluation is performed on the value of each
assignment to a variable with the
\fB-E\fP, \fB-F\fP, or
\fB-i\fP attribute\&.
Assigning a floating point number to a
variable whose type is an integer causes the fractional
part to be truncated\&.
.SS "Prompting\&."
.PP
When used interactively,
the shell prompts with the value of
\fBPS1\fP after expanding it for parameter expansion, command substitution, and
arithmetic substitution,
before reading a command\&.
In addition, each single
\fB!\fP in the prompt is replaced by the command number\&.
A
\fB!!\fP is required to place
\fB!\fP in the prompt\&.
If at any time a new-line is typed and further input is needed
to complete a command, then the secondary prompt
(i\&.e\&., the value of
\fBPS2\fP) is issued\&.
.SS "Conditional Expressions\&."
.PP
A
\fIconditional expression\fP is used with the
\fB[[\fP compound command to test attributes of files and to compare
strings\&.
Field splitting and file name generation are
not performed on the words between
\fB[[\fP and
\fB]]\fP\&. Each expression can be constructed from one or more
of the following unary or binary expressions:
.IP "string" 10
True, if
\fIstring\fP is not null\&.
.IP "-a file" 10
Same is \fB-e\fP below\&.
This is obsolete\&.
.IP "-b file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is a block special file\&.
.IP "-c file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is a character special file\&.
.IP "-d file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is a directory\&.
.IP "-e file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists\&.
.IP "-f file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is an ordinary file\&.
.IP "-g file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is has its setgid bit set\&.
.IP "-k file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is has its sticky bit set\&.
.IP "-n string" 10
True, if length of
\fIstring\fP is non-zero\&.
.IP "-o option" 10
True, if option named
\fIoption\fP is on\&.
.IP "-p file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is a fifo special file or a pipe\&.
.IP "-r file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is readable by current process\&.
.IP "-s file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and has size greater than zero\&.
.IP "-t fildes" 10
True, if file descriptor number
\fIfildes\fP is open and associated with a terminal device\&.
.IP "-u file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is has its setuid bit set\&.
.IP "-w file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is writable by current process\&.
.IP "-x file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is executable by current process\&.
If
\fIfile\fP exists and is a directory, then true if the current process
has permission to search in the directory\&.
.IP "-z string" 10
True, if length of
\fIstring\fP is zero\&.
.IP "-L file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is a symbolic link\&.
.IP "-O file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is owned by the effective user id of this process\&.
.IP "-G file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and its group matches the effective group id of this process\&.
.IP "-S file" 10
True, if
\fIfile\fP exists and is a socket\&.
.IP "file1 -nt file2" 10
True, if
\fIfile1\fP exists and is newer than
\fIfile2\fP\&.
.IP "file1 -ot file2" 10
True, if
\fIfile1\fP exists and is older than
\fIfile2\fP\&.
.IP "file1 -ef file2" 10
True, if
\fIfile1\fP and
\fIfile2\fP exist and refer to the same file\&.
.IP "string == pattern" 10
True, if
\fIstring\fP matches
\fIpattern\fP\&. Any part of
\fIpattern\^\fP can be quoted to cause it to be matched as a string\&.
.IP "string = pattern" 10
Same as \fB==\fP above, but is obsolete\&.
.IP "string != pattern" 10
True, if
\fIstring\fP does not match
\fIpattern\fP\&.
.IP "string1 < string2" 10
True, if
\fIstring1\fP comes before
\fIstring2\fP based on ASCII value of their characters\&.
.IP "string1 > string2" 10
True, if
\fIstring1\fP comes after
\fIstring2\fP based on ASCII value of their characters\&.
.IP "" 10
The following obsolete arithmetic comparisons are also permitted:
.IP "exp1 -eq exp2" 10
True, if
\fIexp1\fP is equal to
\fIexp2\fP\&.
.IP "exp1 -ne exp2" 10
True, if
\fIexp1\fP is not equal to
\fIexp2\fP\&.
.IP "exp1 -lt exp2" 10
True, if
\fIexp1\fP is less than
\fIexp2\fP\&.
.IP "exp1 -gt exp2" 10
True, if
\fIexp1\fP is greater than
\fIexp2\fP\&.
.IP "exp1 -le exp2" 10
True, if
\fIexp1\fP is less than or equal to
\fIexp2\fP\&.
.IP "exp1 -ge exp2" 10
True, if
\fIexp1\fP is greater than or equal to
\fIexp2\fP\&.
.PP
In each of the above expressions, if
\fIfile\fP is of the form
\fB/dev/fd/\fP\fIn\fP,
where
\fIn\fP is an integer,
then the test is applied to the open file whose
descriptor number is
\fIn\fP\&.
.PP
A compound expression can be constructed from these primitives by
using any of the following, listed in decreasing order of precedence\&.
.IP "(expression)" 10
True, if
\fIexpression\fP is true\&.
Used to group expressions\&.
.IP "! expression" 10
True if
\fIexpression\fP is false\&.
.IP "expression1 && expression2" 10
True, if
\fIexpression1\fP and
\fIexpression2\fP are both true\&.
.IP "expression1 \(or\(or expression2" 10
True, if either
\fIexpression1\fP or
\fIexpression2\fP is true\&.
.SS "Input/Output\&."
.PP
Before a command is executed, its input and output
may be redirected using a special notation interpreted by the shell\&.
The following may appear anywhere in a simple-command
or may precede or follow a
\fIcommand\^\fP and are
\fInot\^\fP passed on to the invoked command\&.
Command substitution, parameter expansion,
and arithmetic substitution occur before
\fIword\^\fP or
\fIdigit\^\fP is used except as noted below\&.
File name generation
occurs only if the shell is interactive and
the pattern matches a single file,
Field splitting is not performed\&.
.IP "< word" 10
Use file
\fIword\^\fP as standard input (file descriptor 0)\&.
.IP "> word" 10
Use file
\fIword\^\fP as standard output (file descriptor 1)\&.
If the file does not exist then it is created\&.
If the file exists, and the
\fBnoclobber\fP option is on,
this causes an error;
otherwise, it is truncated to zero length\&.
.IP ">| word" 10
Sames as
\fB>\fP, except that it overrides the
\fBnoclobber\fP option\&.
.IP ">> word" 10
Use file
\fIword\^\fP as standard output\&.
If the file exists then output is appended to it (by first seeking to the end-of-file);
otherwise, the file is created\&.
.IP "<> word" 10
Open file
\fIword\^\fP for reading and writing
as standard input\&.
.IP "<<[-]word" 10
The shell input is read up to a line that is the same as
\fIword\fP after any quoting has been removed remove,
or to an end-of-file\&.
No parameter substitution, command substitution, arithmetic substitution or
file name generation is performed on
\fIword\fP\&. The resulting document,
called a
\fIhere-document\fP, becomes
the standard input\&.
If any character of
\fIword\^\fP is quoted, then no interpretation
is placed upon the characters of the document;
otherwise, parameter expansion, command substitution, and arithmetic
substitution occur,
\fB\enew-line\fP is ignored,
and
\fB\e\fP must be used to quote the characters
\fB\e\fP, \fB$\fP, \fB`\fP\&. If
\fB-\fP is appended to
\fB<<\fP, then all leading tabs are stripped from
\fIword\^\fP and from the document\&.
.IP "<& digit" 10
The standard input is duplicated from file descriptor
\fIdigit\fP (see
\fIdup\fP(2))\&. Similarly for the standard output using
\fB>&\^\fP\fIdigit\fP\&.
.IP "<&-" 10
The standard input is closed\&.
Similarly for the standard output using
\fB>&-\fP\&.
.IP "<&p" 10
The input from the co-process is moved to standard input\&.
.IP ">&p" 10
The output to the co-process is moved to standard output\&.
.IP "" 10
If one of the above is preceded by a digit,
then the
file descriptor number referred to is that specified
by the digit
(instead of the default 0 or 1)\&.
For example:
.IP "" 10
\&.\!\&.\!\&. \!2>&1
.IP "" 10
means file descriptor 2 is to be opened
for writing as a duplicate
of file descriptor 1\&.
.IP "" 10
The order in which redirections are specified is significant\&.
The shell evaluates each redirection in terms of the
(\fIfile descriptor\fP, \fIfile\fP) association at the time of evaluation\&.
For example:
.IP "" 10
\&.\!\&.\!\&. \!1>\fIfname\^\fP 2>&1
.IP "" 10
first associates file descriptor 1 with file
\fIfname\^\fP\&. It then associates file descriptor 2 with the file associated with file
descriptor 1 (i\&.e\&.
\fIfname\^\fP)\&. If the order of redirections were reversed, file descriptor 2 would be associated
with the terminal (assuming file descriptor 1 had been) and then file descriptor
1 would be associated with file
\fIfname\^\fP\&.
.IP "" 10
If a command is followed by
\fB&\fP and job control is not active,
then the default standard input
for the command
is the empty file
\fB/dev/null\fP\&. Otherwise, the environment for the execution of a command contains the
file descriptors of the invoking shell as modified by
input/output specifications\&.
.SS "Environment\&."
.PP
The
\fIenvironment\^\fP (see
\fIenviron\fP(7)) is a list of name-value pairs that is passed to
an executed program in the same way as a normal argument list\&.
The names must be
\fIidentifiers\^\fP and the values are character strings\&.
The shell interacts with the environment in several ways\&.
On invocation, the shell scans the environment
and creates a
variable
for each name found,
giving it the corresponding value and attributes and marking it
\fIexport\fP\&. Executed commands inherit the environment\&.
If the user modifies the values of these
variables
or creates new ones,
using the
\fBexport\fP or
\fBtypeset\fP \fB-x\fP commands they become part of the
environment\&.
The environment seen by any executed command is thus composed
of any name-value pairs originally inherited by the shell,
whose values may be modified by the current shell,
plus any additions
which must be noted in
\fBexport\fP or
\fBtypeset\fP \fB-x\fP commands\&.
.PP
The environment for any
\fIsimple-command\^\fP or function
may be augmented by prefixing it with one or more variable assignments\&.
A variable assignment argument is a word of the form
\fIidentifier=value\fP\&. Thus:
.PP
.nf
\f(CWTERM=450 \!cmd \!args\fR
.fi
.PP
.PP
and
.PP
.nf
\f(CW(export \!TERM; \!TERM=450; \!cmd \!args)\fR
.fi
.PP
.PP
are equivalent (as far as the above execution of
\fIcmd\^\fP is concerned except for special built-in commands listed below -
those that are
preceded with a dagger)\&.
.PP
If the obsolete
\fB-k\fP option is set,
\fIall\^\fP variable assignment arguments are placed in the environment,
even if they occur after the command name\&.
The following
first prints
\fBa=b c\fP and then
\fBc\fP:
.PP
.nf
\f(CWecho a=b c
set ;-k
echo a=b c\fR
.fi
.PP
.PP
This feature is intended for use with scripts written
for early versions of the shell and its use in new scripts
is strongly discouraged\&.
It is likely to disappear someday\&.
.SS "Functions\&."
.PP
For historical reasons, there are two
ways to define functions,
the
\fIname\fP\fB(\^)\fP syntax and
the
\fBfunction\fP \fIname\^\fP syntax, described in the
\fICommands\fP section above\&.
Shell functions are read in and stored internally\&.
Alias names are resolved when the function is read\&.
Functions are executed like commands with the arguments
passed as positional parameters\&.
(See
\fIExecution\fP below\&.)
.PP
Functions defined by the
\fBfunction\fP \fIname\fP syntax and called by name execute in the same process as the caller and
share all files
and present working directory with the
caller\&.
Traps caught by the caller are reset to their default action
inside the function\&.
A trap condition that is not caught or ignored by the
function causes the function to terminate and the condition
to be passed on to the caller\&.
A trap on
\fBEXIT\fP set inside a function
is executed after the function completes in the environment
of the caller\&.
Ordinarily,
variables are shared between the calling program
and the function\&.
However,
the
\fBtypeset\fP special built-in command used within a function
defines local variables whose scope includes
the current function and
all functions it calls\&.
Errors within functions return control to the caller\&.
.PP
Functions defined with the
\fIname\fP\fB(\^)\fP syntax and functions defined with the
\fBfunction\fP \fIname\fP syntax that are invoked with the .
special built-in
are executed in the caller\&'s
environment and share all variables
and traps with the caller\&.
Errors within these function executions cause the script that contains
them to abort\&.
.PP
The special built-in command
\fBreturn\fP is used to return
from function calls\&.
.PP
Function names
can be listed with the
\fB-f\fP or
\fB+f\fP option of the
\fBtypeset\fP special built-in command\&.
The text of functions, when available, will also
be listed with
\fB-f\fP\&. Functions can be undefined with the
\fB-f\fP option of the
\fBunset\fP special built-in command\&.
.PP
Ordinarily, functions are unset when the shell executes a shell script\&.
Functions that need to be defined across separate
invocations of the shell should
be placed in a directory and the
FPATH
variable should contains the name of this directory\&.
They may also
be specified in the
ENV
file\&.
.SS "Jobs\&."
.PP
If the
\fBmonitor\fP option of the
\fBset\fP command is turned on,
an interactive shell associates a \fIjob\fP with each pipeline\&.
It keeps
a table of current jobs, printed by the
\fBjobs\fP command, and assigns them small integer numbers\&.
When a job is started asynchronously with
\fB&\fP, the shell prints a line which looks
like:
.PP
[1] 1234
.PP
indicating that the job which was started asynchronously was job number
1 and had one (top-level) process, whose process id was 1234\&.
.PP
This paragraph and the next require features that are
not in all versions of UNIX and may not apply\&.
If you are running a job and wish to do something else you may hit the key
\fB^Z\fP (control-Z) which sends a STOP signal to the current job\&.
The shell will then normally indicate that the job has been `Stopped\&',
and print another prompt\&.
You can then manipulate the state of this job,
putting it in the background with the
\fBbg\fP command, or run some other
commands and then eventually bring the job back into the foreground with
the foreground command
\fBfg\fP\&. A \fB^Z\fP takes effect immediately and
is like an interrupt in that pending output and unread input are discarded
when it is typed\&.
.PP
A job being run in the background will stop if it tries to read
from the terminal\&.
Background jobs are normally allowed to produce output,
but this can be disabled by giving the command ``stty tostop\&'\&'\&.
If you set this
tty option, then background jobs will stop when they try to produce
output like they do when they try to read input\&.
.PP
There are several ways to refer to jobs in the shell\&.
A job can be referred to by the process id of any process of the job
or by one of the following:
.IP "% number" 10
The job with the given number\&.
.IP "% string" 10
Any job whose command line begins with
\fIstring\fP\&.
.IP "%? string" 10
Any job whose command line contains
\fIstring\fP\&.
.IP "%%" 10
Current job\&.
.IP "%+" 10
Equivalent to
\fB%%\fP\&.
.IP "%-" 10
Previous job\&.
.PP
The shell learns immediately whenever a process changes state\&.
It normally informs you whenever a job becomes blocked so that
no further progress is possible, but only just before it prints
a prompt\&.
This is done so that it does not otherwise disturb your work\&.
The
\fBnotify\fP option causes
the shell to print these job change messages
as soon as they occur\&.
.PP
When the
\fBmonitor\fP option is on, each background job that completes
triggers any trap set for
\fBCHLD\fP\&.
.PP
When you try to leave the shell while jobs are running or stopped, you will
be warned that `You have stopped(running) jobs\&.\&'
You may use the
\fBjobs\fP command to see what they are\&.
If you immediately try to
exit again, the shell will not warn you a second time, and the stopped
jobs will be terminated\&.
When a login shell receives a HUP signal, it sends
a HUP signal to each job that has not been disowned with a the
\fBdisown\fP built-in command described below\&.
.SS "Signals\&."
.PP
The INT and QUIT signals for an invoked
command are ignored if the command is followed by
\fB&\fP and the
\fBmonitor\fP option is not active\&.
Otherwise, signals have the values
inherited by the shell from its parent
(but see also
the
\fBtrap\fP built-in command below)\&.
.SS "Execution\&."
.PP
Each time a command is read, the above substitutions
are carried out\&.
If the command name matches one
of the
\fISpecial built-in Commands\^\fP listed below,
it is executed within the
current shell process\&.
Next, the command name is checked to see if
it matches a user defined function\&.
If it does,
the positional parameters are saved
and then reset to the arguments of the
\fIfunction\^\fP call\&.
When the
\fIfunction\^\fP completes or issues a
\fBreturn\fP, the positional parameter list is restored\&.
For functions defined with the
\fBfunction\fP \fIname\^\fP syntax,
any trap set on
\fBEXIT\fP within the function is executed\&.
The value of a
\fIfunction\^\fP is the value of the last command executed\&.
A function is also executed in the
current shell process\&.
If a command name is not a
\fIspecial built-in command\^\fP or a user defined
\fIfunction\fP, but it is one of the built-in commands listed below
it is executed in the current shell process\&.
.PP
The shell variable
PATHdefines the search path for
the directory containing the command\&.
Alternative directory names are separated by
a colon
(\fB:\fP)\&. The default path is
\fB/bin:/usr/bin:\fP (specifying
\fB/bin\fP, \fB/usr/bin\fP, and the current directory
in that order)\&.
The current directory can be specified by
two or more adjacent colons, or by a colon
at the beginning or end of the path list\&.
If the command name contains a \fB/\fP then the search path
is not used\&.
Otherwise, each directory in the path is
searched for an executable file that is not a directory\&.
If the shell
determines that there is a built-in version
of a command corresponding to a given pathname,
this built-in is invoked in the current process\&.
A process is created and
an attempt is made to execute the command via
\fIexec\fP(2)\&. If the file has execute permission but is not an
\fBa\&.out\fP file,
it is assumed to be a file containing shell commands\&.
A separate shell is spawned to read it\&.
All non-exported variables are removed in this case\&.
If the shell command
file doesn\&'t have read permission,
or if the
\fIsetuid\fP and/or
\fIsetgid\fP bits are set on the file,
then the shell executes an agent whose job it is to
set up the permissions and execute the shell with the
shell command file passed down as an open file\&.
A parenthesized command is executed in
a sub-shell without removing non-exported variables\&.
.SS "Command Re-entry\&."
.PP
The text of the last
HISTSIZE
(default 128)
commands entered from a terminal device
is saved in a
\fIhistory\fP file\&.
The file
\fB$HOME/\&.sh_history\fP is used if the
HISTFILE
variable is not set
or if the file it names is not writable\&.
A shell can access the commands of
all
\fIinteractive\fP shells which use the same named
\fBHISTFILE\fP\&. The built-in command
\fBhist\^\fP is used to list or
edit a portion of this file\&.
The portion of the file to be edited or listed can be selected by
number or by giving the first character or
characters of the command\&.
A single command or range of commands can be specified\&.
If you do not specify an editor program as
an argument to
\fBhist\^\fP then the value of the variable
\fBHISTEDIT\fP is used\&.
If
\fBHISTEDIT\fP is unset, the obsolete variable
\fBFCEDIT\fP is used\&.
If
\fBFCEDIT\fP is not defined then
\fB/bin/ed\fP is used\&.
The edited command(s) is printed and re-executed upon
leaving the editor unless you quit without writing\&.
The
\fB-s\fP option
(
an in obsolete versions, the editor name
\fB-\fP)
is used to skip the editing phase and
to re-execute the command\&.
In this case a substitution parameter of the form
\fIold\fP\fB=\fP\fInew\fP
can be used to modify the command before execution\&.
For example, with the preset alias
\fBr\fP, which is aliased to
\fB\&'hist -s\&'\fP, typing
`\fBr bad=good c\fP\&'
will re-execute the most recent command which starts with the letter
\fBc\fP, replacing the first occurrence of the string
\fBbad\fP with the string
\fBgood\fP\&.
.SS "In-line Editing Options"
.PP
Normally, each command line entered from a terminal device is simply
typed followed by a \fBnew-line\fP (`RETURN\&' or `LINE\ FEED\&')\&.
If either the
\fBemacs\fP, \fBgmacs\fP, or
\fBvi\fP option is active, the user can edit the command line\&.
To be in either of these edit modes
\fBset\fP the corresponding
option\&.
An editing option is automatically selected each time the
\fBVISUAL\fP or
\fBEDITOR\fP variable is assigned a value ending in either of these
option names\&.
.PP
The editing features require that the user\&'s terminal
accept `RETURN\&' as carriage return without line feed
and that a space (`\ \&') must overwrite the current character on
the screen\&.
.PP
The editing modes implement a concept where the user is looking through a
window at the current line\&.
The window width is the value of
\fBCOLUMNS\fP if it is defined, otherwise 80\&.
If the window width is too small to display the prompt and leave
at least 8 columns to enter input, the prompt is truncated from the
left\&.
If the line is longer than the window width minus two, a mark is
displayed at the end of the window to notify the user\&.
As the cursor moves and reaches the window boundaries the window will be
centered about the cursor\&.
The mark is a
\fB>\fP (<, \fB*\fP) if the line extends on the
right (left, both) side(s) of the window\&.
.PP
The search commands in each edit mode provide access to the history file\&.
Only strings are matched, not patterns, although a leading
\fB^\fP in the string restricts the match
to begin at the first character in the line\&.
.PP
Each of the edit modes has an operation to list the files
or commands that match a partially entered word\&.
When applied to the first word on the line,
or the first word after a
\fB;\fP, \fB\(or\fP, \fB&\fP, or
\fB(\fP, and the word does not begin with
\fB\(ap\fP or contain a
\fB/\fP, the list of aliases, functions, and executable commands
defined by the
PATHvariable that could match the partial word is displayed\&.
Otherwise, the list of files that match the given
word is displayed\&.
If the partially entered word does not contain any
file expansion characters, a
\fB*\fP is appended before generating these lists\&.
After displaying the generated list, the input line
is redrawn\&.
These operations are called command name listing and file name listing,
respectively\&.
There are additional operations, referred to as command name
completion and file name completion, which compute the list
of matching commands or files, but instead of printing the list,
replace
the current word with a complete or partial match\&.
For file name completion,
if the match is unique, a
\fB/\fP is appended if the file is a directory and a space is
appended if the file is not a directory\&.
Otherwise, the longest common prefix for all the matching
files replaces the word\&.
For command name completion, only the portion of the file names
after the last
\fB/\fP are used to find the longest command prefix\&.
If only a single name matches this prefix, then the
word is replaced with the command name followed by a space\&.
.SS "Key Bindings\&."
.PP
The
KEYBDtrap can be used to intercept keys as they are typed
and change the characters that are actually seen by
the shell\&.
This trap is executed after each character
( or sequence of characters when the first character is
\fBESC\fP) is entered while reading from a terminal\&.
The variable
\fB\&.sh\&.edchar\fP contains the character or character sequence which
generated the trap\&.
Changing the value of
\fB\&.sh\&.edchar\fP in the trap action causes the shell to behave as if the
new value were entered from the keyboard rather than
the original value\&.
.PP
The variable
\fB\&.sh\&.edcol\fP is set to the input column number of the cursor at the time
of the input\&.
The variable
\fB\&.sh\&.edmode\fP is set to
\fBESC\fP when in vi insert mode (see below) and is null otherwise\&.
By prepending
\fB${\&.sh\&.editmode}\fP to a value assigned to
\fB\&.sh\&.edchar\fP it will cause the shell
to change to control mode if it is not already in this mode\&.
.PP
This trap is not invoked for characters entered as arguments to
editing directives, or while reading input for a character search\&.
.SS "Emacs Editing Mode\&."
.PP
This mode is entered by enabling either the
\fIemacs\fP or
\fIgmacs\fP option\&.
The only difference between these two modes is the way
they handle
\fB^T\fP\&. To edit, the user
moves the cursor to the point needing correction and
then inserts or deletes characters or words as needed\&.
All the editing commands are control characters or escape
sequences\&.
The notation for control characters is caret (
\fB^\fP) followed
by the character\&.
For example,
\fB^F\fP is the notation for control
\fBF\fP\&. This is entered by depressing `f\&' while holding down the
`CTRL\&' (control) key\&.
The `SHIFT\&' key is
\fInot\fP depressed\&.
(The notation
\fB^?\fP indicates the DEL (delete) key\&.)
.PP
The notation for escape sequences is
\fBM-\fP followed by a
character\&.
For example,
\fBM-f\fP (pronounced Meta f)
is entered by depressing ESC
(ascii
\fB033\fP) followed by `f\&'\&.
(\fBM-F\fP would be the notation for ESC followed by `SHIFT\&' (capital) `F\&'\&.)
.PP
All edit commands
operate from any place on the line
(not just at the beginning)\&.
Neither the "RETURN" nor the "LINE FEED" key is
entered after edit commands except when noted\&.
.IP "^F" 10
Move cursor forward (right) one character\&.
.IP "M-f" 10
Move cursor forward one word\&.
(The
\fBemacs\fP editor\&'s idea of a word is a string of characters
consisting of only letters, digits and underscores\&.)
.IP "^B" 10
Move cursor backward (left) one character\&.
.IP "M-b" 10
Move cursor backward one word\&.
.IP "^A" 10
Move cursor to start of line\&.
.IP "^E" 10
Move cursor to end of line\&.
.IP "^] char" 10
Move cursor forward to character
\fIchar\fP on current line\&.
.IP "M-^] char" 10
Move cursor backward to character
\fIchar\fP on current line\&.
.IP "^X^X" 10
Interchange the cursor and mark\&.
.IP "erase" 10
(User defined erase character as defined
by the
\fIstty\fP(1) command, usually
\fB^H\fP or
\fB#\fP\&.) Delete previous character\&.
.IP "^D" 10
Delete current character\&.
.IP "M-d" 10
Delete current word\&.
.IP "M-^H" 10
(Meta-backspace) Delete previous word\&.
.IP "M-h" 10
Delete previous word\&.
.IP "M-^?" 10
(Meta-DEL) Delete previous word (if your interrupt character is
\fB^?\fP (DEL, the default) then this command will not work)\&.
.IP "^T" 10
Transpose current character with next character in
\fIemacs\fP mode\&.
Transpose two previous characters in
\fIgmacs\fP mode\&.
.IP "^C" 10
Capitalize current character\&.
.IP "M-c" 10
Capitalize current word\&.
.IP "M-l" 10
Change the current word to lower case\&.
.IP "^K" 10
Delete from the cursor to the end of the line\&.
If preceded by a numerical parameter whose value is less than the
current cursor position, then delete from given position
up to the cursor\&.
If preceded by a numerical parameter whose value is greater than the
current cursor position, then delete from cursor up to
given cursor position\&.
.IP "^W" 10
Kill from the cursor to the mark\&.
.IP "M-p" 10
Push the region from the cursor to the mark on the stack\&.
.IP "kill" 10
(User defined kill character as defined
by the stty command, usually
\fB^G\fP or
\fB@\fP\&.) Kill the entire current line\&.
If two
\fIkill\fP characters are entered in succession, all
kill characters from then on cause a line feed
(useful when using paper terminals)\&.
.IP "^Y" 10
Restore last item removed from line\&. (Yank item back to the line\&.)
.IP "^L" 10
Line feed and print current line\&.
.IP "^@" 10
(Null character) Set mark\&.
.IP "M- space" 10
(Meta space) Set mark\&.
.IP "^J" 10
(New\ line) Execute the current line\&.
.IP "^M" 10
(Return) Execute the current line\&.
.IP "eof" 10
End-of-file character,
normally
\fB^D\fP, is processed as an End-of-file only
if the current line is null\&.
.IP "^P" 10
Fetch previous command\&.
Each time
\fB^P\fP is entered
the previous command back in time is accessed\&.
Moves back one line when not on the first line of a multi-line command\&.
.IP "M-<" 10
Fetch the least recent (oldest) history line\&.
.IP "M->" 10
Fetch the most recent (youngest) history line\&.
.IP "^N" 10
Fetch next command line\&.
Each time
\fB^N\fP is entered
the next command line forward in time is accessed\&.
.IP "^R string" 10
Reverse search history for a previous command line containing
\fIstring\fP\&. If a parameter of zero is given, the search is forward\&.
\fBString\fR is terminated by a "RETURN" or "NEW\ LINE"\&.
If string is preceded by a
\fB^\fP, the matched line must begin with
\fIstring\fP\&. If
\fIstring\fP is omitted,
then the next command line containing the most recent
\fIstring\fP is accessed\&.
In this case a parameter of zero
reverses the direction of the search\&.
.IP "^O" 10
Operate - Execute the current line and fetch
the next line relative to current line from the
history file\&.
.IP "M- digits" 10
(Escape) Define numeric parameter, the digits
are taken as a parameter to the next command\&.
The commands that accept a parameter are
\fB^F\fP, \fB^B\fP, \fIerase\fP, \fB^C\fP, \fB^D\fP, \fB^K\fP, \fB^R\fP, \fB^P\fP, \fB^N\fP, \fB^]\fP, \fBM-\&.\fP, \fBM-^]\fP, \fBM-_\fP, \fBM-b\fP, \fBM-c\fP, \fBM-d\fP, \fBM-f\fP, \fBM-h\fP, \fBM-l\fP and
\fBM-^H\fP\&.
.IP "M- letter" 10
Soft-key - Your alias list is searched for an
alias by the name
\fB_\fP\fIletter\fP and if an alias of this name is defined, its
value will be inserted on the input queue\&.
The
\fIletter\fP must not be one of the above meta-functions\&.
.IP "M-[ letter" 10
Soft-key - Your alias list is searched for an
alias by the name
\fB__\fP\fIletter\fP and if an alias of this name is defined, its
value will be inserted on the input queue\&.
The can be used to program functions keys on many terminals\&.
.IP "M-\&." 10
The last word of the previous command is inserted
on the line\&.
If preceded by a numeric parameter, the value
of this parameter determines which word to insert rather than
the last word\&.
.IP "M-_" 10
Same as
\fBM-\&.\fP\&.
.IP "M-*" 10
Attempt file name generation on the current word\&.
An asterisk is appended if the word doesn\&'t match any file
or contain any special
pattern characters\&.
.IP "Command or file name completion as described above\&." 10
.IP "M-=" 10
Command or file name listing as described above\&.
.IP "^U" 10
Multiply parameter of next command by 4\&.
.IP "\e" 10
Escape next character\&.
Editing characters, the user\&'s erase, kill and
interrupt (normally
\fB^?\fP) characters
may be entered
in a command line or in a search string if preceded by a
\fB\e\fP\&. The
\fB\e\fP removes the next character\&'s
editing features (if any)\&.
.IP "^V" 10
Display version of the shell\&.
.IP "M-#" 10
If the line does not begin with a
\fB#\fP, a
\fB#\fP is inserted
at the beginning of the line
and after each new-line,
and the line is entered\&.
This causes a comment to be inserted in the history file\&.
If the line begins with a
\fB#\fP, the
\fB#\fP is deleted and one
\fB#\fP after each new-line is also deleted\&.
.SS "Vi Editing Mode\&."
.PP
There are two typing modes\&.
Initially, when you enter a command you are in the
\fIinput\^\fP mode\&.
To edit, the user enters
\fIcontrol\^\fP mode by typing ESC
(\fB033\fP) and moves the cursor to the point needing correction and
then inserts or deletes characters or words as needed\&.
Most control commands accept an optional repeat
\fIcount\fP prior to the command\&.
.PP
When in
\fBvi\fP mode on most systems,
canonical processing is initially enabled and the
command will be echoed again if the speed is 1200 baud or greater and it
contains any control characters or less than one second has elapsed
since the prompt was printed\&.
The ESC character terminates canonical processing for the remainder of the command
and the user can then modify the command line\&.
This scheme has the advantages of canonical processing with the type-ahead
echoing of raw mode\&.
.PP
If the option
\fBviraw\^\fP is also set, the terminal will always have canonical processing
disabled\&.
This mode is implicit for systems that do not support two
alternate end of line delimiters,
and may be helpful for certain terminals\&.
.SS "Input Edit Commands"
.PP
By default the editor is in input mode\&.
.IP "erase" 10
(User defined erase character as defined
by the stty command, usually
\fB^H\fP or
\fB#\fP\&.) Delete previous character\&.
.IP "^W" 10
Delete the previous blank separated word\&.
One some systems the \fBviraw\fP option
may be required for this to work\&.
.IP "eof" 10
As the first character of the line causes
the shell to terminate unless the \fBignoreeof\fP
option is set\&.
Otherwise this character is ignored\&.
.IP "^V" 10
Escape next character\&.
Editing characters and the user\&'s erase or kill
characters may be entered
in a command line or in a search string if preceded by a
\fB^V\fP\&. The
\fB^V\fP removes the next character\&'s
editing features (if any)\&.
One some systems the \fBviraw\fP option
may be required for this to work\&.
.IP "\e" 10
Escape the next
\fIerase\fP or
\fIkill\fP character\&.
.SS "Motion Edit Commands"
.PP
These commands will move the cursor\&.
.IP "[count]l" 10
Cursor forward (right) one character\&.
.IP "[count]w" 10
Cursor forward one alpha-numeric word\&.
.IP "[count]W" 10
Cursor to the beginning of the next word that follows a blank\&.
.IP "[count]e" 10
Cursor to end of word\&.
.IP "[count]E" 10
Cursor to end of the current blank delimited word\&.
.IP "[count]h" 10
Cursor backward (left) one character\&.
.IP "[count]b" 10
Cursor backward one word\&.
.IP "[count]B" 10
Cursor to preceding blank separated word\&.
.IP "[count]\(or" 10
Cursor to column
\fIcount\fP\&.
.IP "[count]fc" 10
Find the next character \fIc\fP in the current line\&.
.IP "[count]Fc" 10
Find the previous character \fIc\fP in the current line\&.
.IP "[count]tc" 10
Equivalent to
\fBf\fP followed by
\fBh\fP\&.
.IP "[count]Tc" 10
Equivalent to
\fBF\fP followed by
\fBl\fP\&.
.IP "[count];" 10
Repeats
\fIcount\fP times,
the last single character find command,
\fBf\fP, \fBF\fP, \fBt\fP, or
\fBT\fP\&.
.IP "[count]," 10
Reverses the last single character find command
\fIcount\fP times\&.
.IP "0" 10
Cursor to start of line\&.
.IP "^" 10
Cursor to first non-blank character in line\&.
.IP "$" 10
Cursor to end of line\&.
.IP "%" 10
Moves to balancing
\fB(\fP, \fB)\fP, \fB{\fP, \fB}\fP, \fB[\fP, or
\fB]\fP\&. If cursor is not on one of the above characters,
the remainder of the line is searched for the first
occurrence of one of the above characters first\&.
.SS "Search Edit Commands"
.PP
These commands access your command history\&.
.IP "[count]k" 10
Fetch previous command\&.
Each time
\fBk\fP is entered
the previous command back in time is accessed\&.
.IP "[count]-" 10
Equivalent to
\fBk\fP\&.
.IP "[count]j" 10
Fetch next command\&.
Each time
\fBj\fP is entered
the next command forward in time is accessed\&.
.IP "[count]+" 10
Equivalent to
\fBj\fP\&.
.IP "[count]G" 10
The command number
\fIcount\fP is fetched\&.
The default is the least recent history command\&.
.IP "/ string" 10
Search backward through history for a previous command containing
\fIstring\fP\&. \fBString\fR is terminated by a "RETURN" or "NEW\ LINE"\&.
If string is preceded by a
\fB^\fP, the matched line must begin with
\fIstring\fP\&. If \fIstring\fP is null the previous string will be used\&.
.IP "? string" 10
Same as
\fB/\fP except that search will be in the forward direction\&.
.IP "n" 10
Search for next match of the last pattern to
\fB/\fP or
\fB?\fP commands\&.
.IP "N" 10
Search for next match of the last pattern to
\fB/\fP or
\fB?\fP, but in reverse direction\&.
.SS "Text Modification Edit Commands"
.PP
These commands will modify the line\&.
.IP "a" 10
Enter input mode and enter text after the current character\&.
.IP "A" 10
Append text to the end of the line\&.
Equivalent to
\fB$a\fP\&.
.IP "[count]cmotion" 10
.IP "c[count]motion" 10
Delete current character through the character that
\fImotion\fP would move the cursor to and enter input mode\&.
If \fImotion\fP is
\fBc\fP, the entire line will be deleted and
input mode entered\&.
.IP "C" 10
Delete the current character through the end of line and enter input mode\&.
Equivalent to
\fBc$\fP\&.
.IP "S" 10
Equivalent to
\fBcc\fP\&.
.IP "D" 10
Delete the current character through the end of line\&.
Equivalent to
\fBd$\fP\&.
.IP "[count]dmotion" 10
.IP "d[count]motion" 10
Delete current character through the character that
\fImotion\fP would move to\&.
If \fImotion\fP is
\fBd\fP, the entire line will be deleted\&.
.IP "i" 10
Enter input mode and insert text before the current character\&.
.IP "I" 10
Insert text before the beginning of the line\&.
Equivalent to
\fB0i\fP\&.
.IP "[count]P" 10
Place the previous text modification before the cursor\&.
.IP "[count]p" 10
Place the previous text modification after the cursor\&.
.IP "R" 10
Enter input mode and
replace characters on the screen with characters you type overlay fashion\&.
.IP "[count]rc" 10
Replace the
\fIcount\fP character(s) starting at the current cursor position with
\fIc\fP, and advance the cursor\&.
.IP "[count]x" 10
Delete current character\&.
.IP "[count]X" 10
Delete preceding character\&.
.IP "[count]\&." 10
Repeat the previous text modification command\&.
.IP "[count]\(ap" 10
Invert the case of the
\fIcount\fP character(s) starting at the current cursor position and advance the cursor\&.
.IP "[count]_" 10
Causes the
\fIcount\^\fP word of the previous command to be appended and
input mode entered\&.
The last word is used
if
\fIcount\^\fP is omitted\&.
.IP "*" 10
Causes an
\fB*\fP to be appended to the current word and file name generation attempted\&.
If no match is found,
it rings the bell\&.
Otherwise, the word is replaced
by the matching pattern and input mode is entered\&.
.IP "\e" 10
Command or file name completion as described above\&.
.SS "Other Edit Commands"
.PP
Miscellaneous commands\&.
.IP "[count]ymotion" 10
.IP "y[count]motion" 10
Yank current character through character that
\fImotion\fP would move the cursor to and puts them into the delete buffer\&.
The text and cursor are unchanged\&.
.IP "Y" 10
Yanks from current position to end of line\&.
Equivalent to
\fBy$\fP\&.
.IP "u" 10
Undo the last text modifying command\&.
.IP "U" 10
Undo all the text modifying commands performed on the line\&.
.IP "[count]v" 10
Returns the command
\fBhist -e ${VISUAL:-${EDITOR:-vi}}\fP \fIcount\fP in the input buffer\&.
If
\fIcount\^\fP is omitted, then the current line is used\&.
.IP "^L" 10
Line feed and print current line\&.
Has effect only in control mode\&.
.IP "^J" 10
(New\ line) Execute the current line, regardless of mode\&.
.IP "^M" 10
(Return) Execute the current line, regardless of mode\&.
.IP "#" 10
If the first character of the command is a
\fB#\fP, then this command deletes this
\fB#\fP and each
\fB#\fP that follows a newline\&.
Otherwise,
sends the line after
inserting a
\fB#\fP in front of each line in the command\&.
Useful for causing the current line to be
inserted in the history as a comment and
uncommenting previously commented commands
in the history file\&.
.IP "=" 10
Command or file name listing as described above\&.
.IP "@ letter" 10
Your alias list is searched for an
alias by the name
\fB_\fP\fIletter\fP and if an alias of this name is defined, its
value will be inserted on the input queue for processing\&.
.SS "Built-in Commands\&."
.PP
The following simple-commands are executed in the shell process\&.
Input/Output redirection is permitted\&.
Unless otherwise indicated, the output is written on file descriptor 1
and the exit status, when there is no syntax error, is zero\&.
Except for
\fB:\fP, \fBtrue\fP, \fBfalse\fP, \fBecho\fP, \fBcommand\fP, \fBnewgrp\fP, and
\fBlogin\fP, all built-in commands accept
\fB--\fP to indicate end of options\&.
They also interpret the option
\fB-?\fP as a help request and print a
\fIusage\^\fP message
on standard error\&.
Commands that are preceded by one or two -
are special built-in commands and
are treated specially in the following ways:
.IP "   1." 6
Variable assignment lists preceding the command
remain in effect when the command completes\&.
.IP "   2." 6
I/O redirections are processed after variable assignments\&.
.IP "   3." 6
Errors
cause a script
that contains them to abort\&.
.IP "   4." 6
They are not valid function names\&.
.IP "   5." 6
Words,
following a command preceded by --
that are in the format of a variable assignment,
are expanded with the same rules as a variable assignment\&.
This means that
tilde substitution is performed after the
\fB=\fP sign and field splitting and file name generation are not
performed\&.
.IP "-: arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
The command only expands parameters\&.
.IP "- \!\&. name\^ arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
If
\fIname\^\fP is a function defined with the
\fBfunction\fP \fIname\^\fP reserved word syntax,
the function is executed in the current environment
( as if it had been defined with the
\fIname\fP\fB()\fP syntax\&.)
Otherwise if
\fIname\^\fP refers to a file, the
file is read in its entirety and the commands are
executed in the current shell environment\&.
The search path
specified by
PATHis used to find the directory containing file\&.
If any arguments
\fIarg\^\fP are given,
they become the positional parameters while processing
the
\&. command and are restored upon completion\&.
Otherwise the positional parameters are unchanged\&.
The exit status is the exit status of the last command executed\&.
.IP "-- alias -ptx name =value\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
\fBalias\^\fP with no arguments prints the list of aliases
in the form
\fIname=value\^\fP on standard output\&.
The
\fB-p\fP option
causes the word
\fBalias\fP to be inserted before each one\&.
When one or more arguments are given
an
\fIalias\^\fP is defined
for each
\fIname\^\fP whose
\fIvalue\^\fP is given\&.
A trailing space in
\fIvalue\^\fP causes the next word to be checked for
alias substitution\&.
The obsolete
\fB-t\fP option is used to set and list tracked aliases\&.
The value of a tracked alias is the full pathname
corresponding to the given
\fIname\fP\&. The value becomes undefined when the value of
\fBPATH\fP is reset but the alias remains tracked\&.
Without the
\fB-t\fP option,
for each
\fIname\^\fP in the argument list
for which no
\fIvalue\^\fP is given, the name
and value of the alias is printed\&.
The obsolete
\fB-x\fP option has no effect\&.
The exit status is non-zero if a
\fIname\^\fP is given, but no value, and no alias has been defined for the
\fIname\^\fP\&.
.IP "bg job\^\&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
This command is only on systems that support job control\&.
Puts each specified
\fIjob\^\fP into the background\&.
The current job is put in the background
if
\fIjob\^\fP is not specified\&.
See
\fIJobs\fP for a description of the format of
\fIjob\fP\&.
.IP "- break n\^" 10
Exit from the enclosing
\fBfor\^\fP, \fBwhile\^\fP, \fBuntil\^\fP, or
\fBselect\^\fP loop, if any\&.
If
\fIn\^\fP is specified then break
\fIn\^\fP levels\&.
.IP "builtin -ds -f file\^ name\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
If
\fIname\^\fP is not specified, the built-ins are printed on standard output\&.
The
\fB-s\fP option prints only the special built-ins\&.
Otherwise, each
\fIname\^\fP represents the pathname whose basename is the name of the built-in\&.
The entry point function name is determined by prepending
\fBb_\fP to the built-in name\&.
Special built-ins cannot be bound to a pathname or deleted\&.
The
\fB-d\fP option deletes each of the given built-ins\&.
On systems that support dynamic loading, the
\fB-f\fP option names a shared library containing the code for built-ins\&.
Once a library is loaded, its symbols become available
for subsequent invocations of
\fBbuiltin\fP\&. Multiple libraries can be specified with separate invocations
of the \fBbuiltin\fP command\&.
Libraries are searched in the reverse order in which they are specified\&.
.IP "" 10
Each command that is to be built-in must be written as a C function whose name is of the form
\fBb_funcName\fP, where \fBfuncName\fP is the name of the built-in
to be added\&. This function has the same argument calling convention as \&'main\&' (i\&.e\&. \fBargc\fP
and \fBargv\fP\(em a list of strings)\&.  The \fBb_funcName\fP parses and
error-checks the incoming arguments and then calls the real \fBfuncName\fP function\&.
.IP "cd -LP arg\^" 10
.IP "cd -LP old\^ new\^" 10
This command can be in either of two forms\&.
In the first form it
changes the current directory to
\fIarg\fP\&. If
\fIarg\^\fP is
\fB-\fP the directory is changed to the previous
directory\&.
The shell
variable
HOMEis the default
\fIarg\fP\&. The variable
\fBPWD\fP is set to the current directory\&.
The shell variable
CDPATHdefines the search path for
the directory containing
\fIarg\fP\&. Alternative directory names are separated by
a colon
(\fB:\fP)\&. The default path is
\fB<null>\fP (specifying the current directory)\&.
Note that the current directory is specified by a null path name,
which can appear immediately after the equal sign
or between the colon delimiters anywhere else in the path list\&.
If
\fIarg\fP begins with a \fB/\fP then the search path
is not used\&.
Otherwise, each directory in the path is
searched for
\fIarg\fP\&.
.IP "" 10
The obsolete second form of
\fBcd\fP substitutes the string
\fInew\fP for the string
\fIold\fP in the current directory name,
\fBPWD\fP and tries to change to this new directory\&.
.IP "" 10
By default, symbolic links are not followed when
finding the directory name\&.
This is equivalent to the
\fB-L\fP option\&.
The
\fB-P\fP option causes
symbolic links to be followed when determining the directory\&.
The last instance of
\fB-L\fP or
\fB-P\fP determines which method is used\&.
.IP "" 10
The
\fBcd\^\fP command may not be executed by
\fBrksh\^\&.\fP
.IP "command -pvV name\^ arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Without the
\fB-v\fP or
\fB-V\fP options,
\fBcommand\fP executes
\fIname\^\fP with the arguments given by
\fIarg\fP\&. The
\fB-p\fP option causes
a default path to be searched
rather than the one defined by the value of
\fBPATH\fP\&. Functions will not be searched for when finding
\fIname\fP\&. In addition, if
\fIname\^\fP refers to a special built-in,
none of the special properties associated with the leading
daggers will be honored\&.
(
For example, the predefined alias
\fBredirect=\&'command exec\&'\fP prevents a script from terminating when an invalid
redirection is given\&.)
With the
\fB-v\fP option,
\fBcommand\fP is equivalent to the built-in
\fBwhence\fP command described below\&.
The
\fB-V\fP options, causes
\fBcommand\fP to
\fBwhence -v\fP\&.
.IP "- continue n\^" 10
Resume the next iteration of the enclosing
\fBfor\^\fP, \fBwhile\^\fP, \fBuntil\^\fP, or
\fBselect\^\fP loop\&.
If
\fIn\^\fP is specified then resume at the
\fIn\fP-th enclosing loop\&.
.IP "disown job\^\&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Causes the shell not to send a HUP signal to
each given
\fIjob\fP, or all active jobs if
\fIjob\fP is omitted,
when a login shell terminates\&.
.IP "echo arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
When the first
\fIarg\^\fP does not begin with a -, and
none of the arguments contain a \e,
then
\fBecho\fP prints each of its arguments separated by a space
and terminated by a new-line\&.
Otherwise, the behavior of
\fBecho\fP is system dependent
and
\fBprint\fP or
\fBprintf\fP described below should be used\&.
See
\fIecho\fP(1) for usage and description\&.
.IP "- eval arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
The arguments are read as input
to the shell
and the resulting command(s) executed\&.
.IP "- exec -c -a name\^ arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
If
\fIarg\^\fP is given,
the command specified by
the arguments is executed in place of this shell
without creating a new process\&.
The
\fB-c\fP option causes the environment to be cleared before applying
variable assignments associated with the
\fBexec\fP invocation\&.
The
\fB-a\fP option
causes
\fIname\^\fP rather than the first
\fIarg\fP, to become
\fBargv[0]\fP for the new process\&.
Input/output arguments may appear and
affect the current process\&.
If
\fIarg\^\fP is not given
the effect of this command is to
modify file descriptors
as prescribed by the input/output redirection list\&.
In this case,
any file descriptor numbers greater than 2 that are
opened with this mechanism are closed when invoking
another program\&.
.IP "- exit n\^" 10
Causes the shell to exit
with the exit status specified by
\fIn\fP\&. The value will be the least significant 8 bits of the specified status\&.
If
\fIn\^\fP is omitted then the exit status is that of the last command executed\&.
An end-of-file will also cause the shell to exit
except for a
shell which has the
\fIignoreeof\fP option (see
\fBset\fP below) turned on\&.
.IP "-- export -p name\^=value\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
If
\fIname\^\fP is not given,
the names and values of each variable with
the export attribute are printed with the values
quoted in a manner that allows them to be re-inputed\&.
The
\fB-p\fP option
causes the word
\fBexport\fP to be inserted before each one\&.
Otherwise, the given
\fIname\fPs are marked for automatic
export to the
\fIenvironment\^\fP of subsequently-executed commands\&.
.IP "fg job\^\&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
This command is only on systems that support job control\&.
Each
\fIjob\^\fP specified is brought to the foreground and waited for in
the specified order\&.
Otherwise, the current job is
brought into the foreground\&.
See
\fIJobs\fP for a description of the format of
\fIjob\fP\&.
.IP "getconf name\^ pathname\^" 10
Prints the current value of the configuration parameter given by
\fIname\fP\&.
.IP "getopts optstring vname\^ arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Checks
\fIarg\fP for legal options\&.
If
\fIarg\fP is omitted,
the positional parameters are used\&.
An option argument begins with a
\fB+\fP or a
\fB-\fP\&. An option not beginning with
\fB+\fP or
\fB-\fP or the argument
\fB-\!-\fP ends the options\&.
\fIoptstring\fP contains the letters that
\fIgetopts\fP recognizes\&.
If a letter is followed by a
\fB:\fP, that option is expected to have an argument\&.
The options can be separated from the argument by blanks\&.
.IP "" 10
\fBgetopts
places the next option letter it finds inside variable\fP \fIvname\^\fP each time it is invoked with a
\fB+\fP prepended when
\fIarg\fP begins with a
\fB+\fP\&. The index of the next
\fIarg\fP is stored in
\fBOPTIND\fP\&. The option argument,
if any,
gets stored in
\fBOPTARG\fP\&.
.IP "" 10
A leading
\fB:\fP in
\fIoptstring\fP causes
\fBgetopts\fP to store the letter of an invalid
option in
\fBOPTARG\fP, and to set
\fIvname\fP to
\fB?\fP for an unknown option and to
\fB:\fP when a required option is missing\&.
Otherwise,
\fBgetopts\fP prints an error message\&.
The exit status is non-zero when there are no more options\&.
.IP "" 10
There is no way to specify any of the options
\fB:\fP, \fB+\fP, \fB-\fP, \fB?\fP, \fB[\fP, and
\fB]\fP\&. The option
\fB#\fP can only be specified as the first option\&.
.IP "hist -e ename\^ \  -nlr\^ first\^ last\^" 10
.IP "hist -s old=new\^ command\^" 10
In the first form,
a range of commands from
\fIfirst\^\fP to
\fIlast\^\fP is selected from the last
\fBHISTSIZE\fP commands that were typed at the terminal\&.
The arguments
\fIfirst\^\fP and
\fIlast\^\fP may be specified as a number or as a string\&.
A string is used to locate the most recent command starting with
the given string\&.
A negative number is used as an offset to the current command number\&.
If the
\fB-l\fP option
is selected,
the commands are listed on standard output\&.
Otherwise, the editor program
\fIename\^\fP is invoked on a file containing these
keyboard commands\&.
If
\fIename\^\fP is not supplied, then the value of the variable
\fBHISTEDIT\fP is used\&.
If
\fBHISTEDIT\fP is not set then
\fBFCEDIT\fP (default
\fB/bin/ed\^\fP) is used as the editor\&.
When editing is complete, the edited command(s)
is executed if the changes have been saved\&.
If
\fIlast\^\fP is not specified
then it will be set to
\fIfirst\fP\&. If
\fIfirst\^\fP is not specified
the default is the previous command
for editing and -16 for listing\&.
The option
\fB-r\fP reverses the order of the commands and
the option
\fB-n\fP suppresses command numbers when listing\&.
In the second form the
\fIcommand\^\fP is re-executed after the substitution
\fIold\^\fP\fB=\fP\fInew\^\fP
is performed\&.
.IP "jobs -lnp\^ job\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Lists information about each given job; or all active jobs if
\fIjob\fP is omitted\&.
The
\fB-l\fP option lists process ids in addition to the normal information\&.
The
\fB-n\fP option only displays jobs that have stopped or exited since last
notified\&.
The
\fB-p\fP option causes only the process group to be listed\&.
See
\fIJobs\fP for a description of the format of
\fIjob\fP\&.
.IP "kill -s signame\^ job\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
.IP "kill -n signum\^ job\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
.IP "kill -l sig\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Sends either the TERM (terminate) signal or the
specified signal to the specified jobs or processes\&.
Signals are either given by number with the
\fB-n\fP option or by name with the
\fB-s\fP option
(as given in
\fB<signal\&.h>\fP, stripped of the prefix ``SIG\&'\&' with
the exception that SIGCLD is named CHLD)\&.
For backward compatibility, the
\fBn\fP and
\fBs\fP can be omitted and the number or name placed immediately
after the
\fB-\fP\&. If the signal being sent is TERM (terminate) or HUP (hangup),
then the job or process will be sent a CONT (continue) signal
if it is stopped\&.
The argument
\fIjob\^\fP can be the process id of a process that is not a member of one of the
active jobs\&.
See
\fIJobs\fP for a description of the format of
\fIjob\fP\&. In the third form,
\fBkill -l\fP, if
\fIsig\^\fP is not specified,
the signal names are listed\&.
Otherwise, for each
\fIsig\^\fP that is a name, the corresponding signal number is listed\&.
For each
\fIsig\^\fP that is a number, the signal name corresponding to the
least significant 8 bits of
\fIsig\^\fP is listed\&.
.IP "let arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Each
\fIarg\fP is a separate
\fIarithmetic expression\fP to be evaluated\&.
See
\fIArithmetic Evaluation\fP above, for a description of arithmetic expression evaluation\&.
.IP "" 10
The exit status is
0 if the value of the last expression
is non-zero, and 1 otherwise\&.
.IP "- newgrp arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
Equivalent to
\fBexec /bin/newgrp\fP \fIarg\^\fP \&.\!\&.\!\&.\^\&.
.IP "print -Rnprs\^ -u unit\^ -f format\^ arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
With no options or with option
\fB-\fP or
\fB-\!-\fP, Each
\fIarg\fP is printed
on standard output\&.
The
\fB-f\fP option causes the arguments to be printed as
described by
\fBprintf\fP\&. In this case any
\fBn\fP, \fBr\fP, \fBR\fP options are ignored\&.
Otherwise,
unless the
\fB-R\fP or
\fB-r\fP, are specified, the following
escape conventions will be applied:
.RS
.IP "\ea" 10
The alert character (ascii
\fB07\fP)\&.
.IP "\eb" 10
The backspace character (ascii
\fB010\fP)\&.
.IP "\ec" 10
Causes
\fBprint\fP to end without processing more arguments and
not adding a new-line\&.
.IP "\ef" 10
The formfeed character (ascii
\fB014\fP)\&.
.IP "\en" 10
The new-line character (ascii
\fB012\fP)\&.
.IP "\er" 10
The carriage return character (ascii
\fB015\fP)\&.
.IP "\et" 10
The tab character (ascii
\fB011\fP)\&.
.IP "\ev" 10
The vertical tab character (ascii
\fB013\fP)\&.
.IP "\eE" 10
The escape character (ascii
\fB033\fP)\&.
.IP "\e\e" 10
The backslash character \e\&.
.RE
.IP "" 10
The
\fB-R\fP option will print all subsequent arguments and options
other than
\fB-n\fP\&. The
\fB-p\fP option causes the
arguments to be written onto the pipe
of the process spawned with
\fB\(or&\fP instead of standard output\&.
The
\fB-s\fP option causes the
arguments to be written onto the history file
instead of standard output\&.
The
\fB-u\fP option can be used to specify a one digit
file descriptor unit number
\fIunit\^\fP on which the
output will be placed\&.
The default is 1\&.
If the option
\fB-n\fP is used, no
\fBnew-line\^\fP is added to the output\&.
.IP "printf format\^ arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
The arguments
\fIarg\^\fP are printed on standard output
in accordance with the ANSI-C
formatting rules associated with the format string
\fIformat\fP\&. The following extensions can also be used:
.RS
.IP "   \(bu" 6
A
\fB%b\fP format can be used instead of
\fB%s\fP to cause escape sequences in the corresponding
\fIarg\^\fP to be expanded as described in
\fBprint\&.\fP
.IP "   \(bu" 6
A
\fB%P\fP format can be used instead of
\fB%s\fP to cause
\fIarg\^\fP to be interpreted as an extended regular
expression and be printed as a shell pattern\&.
.IP "   \(bu" 6
A
\fB%q\fP format can be used instead of
\fB%s\fP to cause the resulting string to be quoted in a manner than can
be reinput to the shell\&.
.IP "   \(bu" 6
The precision field of the
\fB%d\fP format can be followed by a
\&. and the output base\&.
.RE
.IP "pwd -LP" 10
Outputs the value of the current working
directory\&.
If the
\fB-P\fP option is given,
all symbolic links are resolved from the name\&.
.IP "read -Aprs\^ -d delim\^ -t timeout\^ -u unit\^ vname?prompt\^ vname\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
The shell input mechanism\&.
One line is read and
is broken up into fields using the characters in
IFSas separators\&.
The escape character,
\fB\e\fP, is used to remove any special meaning for the next
character and for line continuation\&.
The
\fB-d\fP option
causes the read to continue to the first character of
\fIdelim\^\fP rather than new-line\&.
In raw mode,
\fB-r,\fP the
\fB\e\fP character is not treated specially\&.
The first
field is assigned to the first
\fIvname\fP, the second field
to the second
\fIvname\fP, etc\&., with leftover fields assigned to the last
\fIvname\fP\&. The
\fB-A\fP option causes the variable
\fIvname\^\fP to be unset and each field that is read to be stored in
successive elements of the indexed array
\fIvname\&.\fP The
\fB-p\fP option causes the input line
to be taken from the input pipe
of a process spawned by the shell
using
\fB\(or&\fP\&. If the
\fB-s\fP option is present,
the input will be saved as a command in the history file\&.
The option
\fB-u\fP can be used to specify a one digit file
descriptor unit
\fIunit\^\fP to read from\&.
The file descriptor can be opened with the
\fBexec\^\fP special built-in command\&.
The default value of unit
\fIn\^\fP is 0\&.
The option
\fB-t\fP is used to specify a timeout in decimal
seconds when reading from a terminal or pipe\&.
If
\fIvname\^\fP is omitted then
\fBREPLY\fP is used as the default
\fIvname\fP\&. An end-of-file with the
\fB-p\fP option causes cleanup for this process
so that another can be spawned\&.
If the first argument contains a
\fB?\fP, the remainder of this word is used as a
\fIprompt\^\fP on standard error
when the shell is interactive\&.
The exit status is 0 unless an end-of-file is encountered
or read has timed out\&.
.IP "-- readonly -p vname=value\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
If
\fIvname\^\fP is not given
the names and values of each variable with
the readonly attribute is printed with the values
quoted in a manner that allows them to be re-inputed\&.
The
\fB-p\fP option
causes the word
\fBreadonly\fP to be inserted before each one\&.
Otherwise, the given
\fIvname\fPs are marked
readonly and these
names cannot be changed
by subsequent assignment\&.
.IP "- return n\^" 10
Causes a shell
\fIfunction\fP or
\fB\!\&.\fP
script to return
to the invoking script
with the return status specified by
\fIn\fP\&. The value will be the least significant 8 bits of the specified status\&.
If
\fIn\^\fP is omitted then the return status is that of the last command executed\&.
If
\fBreturn\fP is invoked while not in a
\fIfunction\fP or a
\fB\!\&.\fP
script,
then it behaves the same as
\fBexit\fP\&.
.IP "- set \(+-CPabefhkmnopstuvx \(+-o option\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&. \(+-A vname\^ arg\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
The options for this command have meaning as follows:
.RS
.IP "-A" 10
Array assignment\&.
Unset the variable
\fIvname\fP and assign values sequentially from the
list
\fIarg\fP\&. If
\fB+A\fP is used, the variable
\fIvname\fP is not unset first\&.
.IP "-C" 10
Prevents redirection
\fB>\fP from truncating existing files\&.
Files that are created are opened with the O_EXCL mode\&.
Require
\fB>\(or\fP to truncate a file when turned on\&.
.IP "-P" 10
Causes the
\fBcd\fP and
\fBpwd\fP built-in commands to default to physical mode\&.
.IP "-a" 10
All subsequent variables that are defined are automatically exported\&.
.IP "-b" 10
Prints job completion messages as soon as a background job changes
state rather than waiting for the next prompt\&.
.IP "-e" 10
If a command has a non-zero exit status,
execute the
\fBERR\fP trap, if set,
and exit\&.
This mode is disabled while reading profiles\&.
.IP "-f" 10
Disables file name generation\&.
.IP "-h" 10
Each command
becomes a tracked alias when first encountered\&.
.IP "-k" 10
(Obsolete)\&. All variable assignment arguments are placed in the environment for a command,
not just those that precede the command name\&.
.IP "-m" 10
Background jobs will run in a separate process group
and a line will print upon completion\&.
The exit status of background jobs is reported in a completion message\&.
On systems with job control,
this option is turned on automatically for
interactive shells\&.
.IP "-n" 10
Read commands and check them for syntax errors, but do not execute them\&.
Ignored for interactive shells\&.
.IP "-o" 10
The following argument can be one of the following option names:
.RS
.IP "allexport" 10
Same as
\fB-a\fP\&.
.IP "errexit" 10
Same as
\fB-e\fP\&.
.IP "bgnice" 10
All background jobs are run at a lower priority\&.
This is the default mode\&.
.IP "emacs" 10
Puts you in an
\fIemacs\fP style in-line editor for command entry\&.
.IP "gmacs" 10
Puts you in a
\fIgmacs\fP style in-line editor for command entry\&.
.IP "ignoreeof" 10
The shell will not exit on end-of-file\&.
The command
\fBexit\fP must be used\&.
.IP "keyword" 10
Same as
\fB-k\fP\&.
.IP "markdirs" 10
All directory names resulting from file name generation have a trailing
\fB/\fP appended\&.
.IP "monitor" 10
Same as
\fB-m\fP\&.
.IP "noclobber" 10
Same as
\fB-C\fP\&.
.IP "noexec" 10
Same as
\fB-n\fP\&.
.IP "noglob" 10
Same as
\fB-f\fP\&.
.IP "nolog" 10
Do not save function definitions in history file\&.
.IP "notify" 10
Same as
\fB-b\fP\&.
.IP "nounset" 10
Same as
\fB-u\fP\&.
.IP "physical" 10
Same as
\fB-P\fP\&.
.IP "privileged" 10
Same as
\fB-p\fP\&.
.IP "verbose" 10
Same as
\fB-v\fP\&.
.IP "trackall" 10
Same as
\fB-h\fP\&.
.IP "vi" 10
Puts you in insert mode of a
\fIvi\^\fP style in-line editor
until you hit escape character
\fB033\fP\&. This puts you in control mode\&.
A return sends the line\&.
.IP "viraw" 10
Each character is processed as it is typed
in
\fIvi\^\fP mode\&.
.IP "xtrace" 10
Same as
\fB-x\fP\&.
.IP "If no option name is supplied then the current option settings are printed\&." 10
.RE
.IP "-p" 10
Disables processing of the
\fB$HOME/\&.profile\fP file and uses the file
\fB/etc/suid_profile\fP instead of the
\fBENV\fP file\&.
This mode is on whenever the effective uid (gid)
is not equal to the real uid (gid)\&.
Turning this off causes the effective uid and gid to be
set to the real uid and gid\&.
.IP "-s" 10
Sort the positional parameters lexicographically\&.
.IP "-t" 10
(Obsolete)\&. Exit after reading and executing one command\&.
.IP "-u" 10
Treat unset parameters as an error when substituting\&.
.IP "-v" 10
Print shell input lines as they are read\&.
.IP "-x" 10
Print commands and their arguments as they are executed\&.
.IP "-\!-" 10
Do not change any of the options; useful in setting
\fB$1\fP to a value beginning with
\fB-\fP\&. If no arguments follow this option then the positional parameters are unset\&.
.IP "" 10
As an obsolete feature,
if the first
\fIarg\^\fP is
\fB-\fP then the
\fB-x\fP and
\fB-v\fP options are turned off and the next
\fIarg\fP is treated as the first argument\&.
Using
\fB+\fP rather than
\fB-\fP causes these options to be turned off\&.
These options can also be used upon invocation of the shell\&.
The current set of options may be found in
\fB$-\fP\&. Unless
\fB-A\fP is specified,
the remaining arguments are positional
parameters and are assigned, in order, to
\fB$1\fP \fB$2\fP \&.\!\&.\!\&.\^\&.
If no arguments are given then the names and values
of all variables are printed on the standard output\&.
.RE
.IP "- shift n\^" 10
The positional parameters from
\fB$\fP\fIn\fP\fB+1\fP
\&.\!\&.\!\&.
are renamed
\fB$1\fP \&.\!\&.\!\&.\^
, default
\fIn\^\fP is 1\&.
The parameter
\fIn\^\fP can be any arithmetic expression that evaluates to a non-negative
number less than or equal to
\fB$#\fP\&.
.IP "sleep seconds\^" 10
Suspends execution for the number of decimal seconds or fractions of a
second given by
\fIseconds\fP\&.
.IP "- trap -p action\^ sig\^ \&.\!\&.\!\&." 10
The -p
option causes the trap
action associated with each trap as specified by the arguments
to be printed with appropriate quoting\&.
Otherwise,
\fIaction\^\fP will be processed as if it were an argument to
\fBeval\fP when the shell
receives signal(s)
\fIsig\fP\&. Each
\fIsig\^\fP can be given as a number or as the name of the signal\&.
Trap commands are executed in order of signal number\&.
Any attempt to set a trap on a signal that
was ignored on entry to the current shell
is ineffective\&.
If
\fIaction\^\fP is omitted and the first
\fIsig\^\fP is a number, or if
\fIaction\^\fP is
\fB-\fP, then the trap(s) for each
\fIsig\^\fP are reset
to their original values\&.
If
