.SS "Invocation\&."
.PP
If the shell is invoked by
\fIexec\fP(2), and the first character of argument zero
(\fB$0\fP) is
\fB-\fP, then the shell is assumed to be a
\fIlogin\fP shell and
commands are read from
\fB/etc/profile\fP and then from either
\fB\&.profile\fP in the current directory or
\fB$HOME/\&.profile\fP, if either file exists\&.
Next, commands are read from
the file named by
performing parameter expansion, command substitution,
and arithmetic substitution on
the value of the environment variable
\fBENV\fP if the file exists\&.
If the
\fB-s\fP option is not present and
\fIarg\^\fP is, then a path search is performed on the first
\fIarg\^\fP to determine the name of the script to execute\&.
The script
\fIarg\^\fP must have read permission and any
\fIsetuid\fP and
\fIgetgid\fP settings will be ignored\&.
If the script is not found on the path,
\fIarg\^\fP is processed as if it named a built-in command or function\&.
Commands are then read as described below;
the following option are interpreted by the shell
when it is invoked:
.IP "-c" 10
If the
\fB-c\fP option is present then
commands are read from the first
\fIarg\fP\&. Any remaining arguments become
position parameters starting at
\fB0\fP\&.
.IP "-s" 10
If the
\fB-s\fP option is present or if no
arguments remain
then commands are read from the standard input\&.
Shell output,
except for the output of the
\fISpecial\fP \fICommands\^\fP listed above,
is written to
file descriptor 2\&.
.IP "-i" 10
If the
\fB-i\fP option is present or
if the shell input and output are attached to a terminal (as told by
\fIioctl\fP(2)) then this shell is
\fIinteractive\fP\&. In this case TERM is ignored (so that \fBkill 0\fP
does not kill an interactive shell) and INTR is caught and ignored
(so that
\fBwait\fP is interruptible)\&.
In all cases, QUIT is ignored by the shell\&.
.IP "-r" 10
If the
\fB-r\fP option is present the shell is a restricted shell\&.
.PP
The
\fB-I\fP \fIfilename\^\fP option is used
to generate a cross reference database
that can be used by a separate utility
to find definitions and references for variables and commands\&.
.PP
The remaining options and arguments are described under the
\fBset\fP command above\&.
An optional
\fB-\fP as the first argument is ignored\&.
.SS "Rksh Only"
.PP
\fIRksh\fP is used to set up login names and execution environments whose
capabilities are more controlled than those of the standard shell\&.
The actions of
\fBrksh\fP are identical to those of
\fBksh\fP, except that the following are disallowed:
.IP "" 10
changing directory (see
\fIcd\fP(1))
.IP "" 10
setting or unsetting the value or attributes of
\fBSHELL\fP, \fBENV\fP, or
\fBPATH\fP
.IP "" 10
specifying path or
command names containing
\fB/\fP
.IP "" 10
redirecting output
(\fB>\fP, \fB>|\fP, \fB<>\fP, and
\fB>>\fP)
.PP
The restrictions above are enforced
after \fB\&.profile\fP and the
\fBENV\fP files are interpreted\&.
.PP
When a command to be executed is found to be a shell procedure,
invokes
\fIsh\^}\fP {\&.B rksh\^
invokes
\fIksh\^}\fP to execute it\&.
Thus, it is possible to provide to the end-user shell procedures
that have access to the full power of
the standard shell,
while imposing a limited menu of commands;
this scheme assumes that the end-user does not have write and
execute permissions in the same directory\&.
.PP
The net effect of these rules is that the writer of the
\fB\&.profile\fP has complete control over user actions,
by performing guaranteed setup actions
and leaving the user in an appropriate directory
(probably
\fInot\^\fP the login directory)\&.
.PP
The system administrator often sets up a directory
of commands
(i\&.e\&.,
\fB/usr/rbin\fP) that can be safely invoked by
\fBrksh\fP\&.
.SH "EXIT"
.PP
Errors detected by the shell, such as syntax errors,
cause the shell
to return a non-zero exit status\&.
Otherwise, the shell returns the exit status of
the last command executed (see also the
\fBexit\fP command above)\&.
If the shell is being used non-interactively
then execution of the shell file is abandoned\&.
Run time errors detected by the shell are reported by
printing the command or function name and the error condition\&.
If the line number that the error occurred on is greater than one,
then the line number is also printed in square brackets
(\fB[]\fP) after the command or function name\&.
